{Welcome, dear chess players, to this new project, "Spanish for White." The Spanish is one of the most fascinating openings in chess theory, and for more than 150 years, it was constantly used by the world's top players. In this first database, GM Baadur Jobava and I will analyze Black's most classical continuations: The Berlin, The Open Spanish, and the Classical Spanish 3...a6 4.Ba4 Nf6 5.00 Be7.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 (3... Nf6 {The Berlin is one of Black's most solid continuations, and I have analyzed it from the Black side in my Modern Chess database "Berlin for Black".} 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1 Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bf1 Nxe5 (7... Nf5 {Black wants to keep more pieces on the board, and this was also my recommendation for the Black's side. We will analyze it in Chapter 18.}) 8. Rxe5 O-O 9. d4 Bf6 10. Re2 $5 {Is my recommendation. Against 10.Re2, Black cannot play as he usually does against 10.Re1. For example, the standard 10...Re8 is not so great here and we will speak about it in Chapter 14.} Nc4 $5 {Kramnik's idea that he played in his last classical tournament, Tata 2019. We will analyze it in Chapter 17.} (10... Nf5 {Will be analyzed in Chapter 15.}) (10... b6 {Is Black's most common continuation, and we will analyze it in Chapter 16.})) 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 {The Classical Spanish is one of Black's most solid continuations.} (5... Nxe4 {This is the Classical Spanish, one of Black's most concrete variations. 6.d4!? Is White's big main line, but we will focus on the more rare} 6. Re1 $5 {And GM Baadur Jobava analyzes it in Chapters 12 and 13.}) 6. d3 $5 {Instead of going for the mainstream 6.Re1, we will focus on the fresher 6.d3.} b5 (6... d6 {is another possible move order, and our suggestion against it is} 7. c4 $5 {GM Baadur Jobava will explain the ideas of this move in Chapter 11.}) 7. Bb3 d6 8. a3 O-O (8... a5 $5 {And other sidelines, will be analyzed in Chapter 10.}) 9. Nc3 {This is the starting position of our main Classical Spanish. This direction is practically more interesting than the mainstream 6.Re1 because we have only 2.000 games instead of the 200.000 of the mainline! Black has a lot of possible continuations, and we will analyze them separately.} Bg4 {[%cal Gc6d4] This is Black's most common continuation.} (9... Bb7 {This move is in the "Zaitsev spirit". We will analyze it in Chapter 2.}) (9... Nb8 {This move is in the "Breyer spirit", we will analyze it in Chapter 3.}) (9... Be6 {This is a very logical move, and we will analyze it in Chapter 4.}) (9... Na5 {This move is in the "Chigorin spirit", and we will analyze it in Chapter 5.}) (9... Rb8 $5 {Nowadays, this is a popular move at the high level. We will analyze it, together with 9...h6, in Chapter 6. For example, we will speak about the very recent game Giri-Gukesh, played in August 2024 at the Sinquifield Cup.}) 10. Be3 Nd4 11. Bxd4 exd4 12. Nd5 {We will introduce this position and check the moves 12...Nd7, 12...c6 and 12...h6 in Chapter 7.} Nxd5 {Aronian's defense.} (12... c5 {This is the "Ding defense" and we will analyze it in Chapter 8.}) 13. Bxd5 {Black can now play 13...Rb8 or 13...Rc8, and we will analyze it in Chapter 9. As always, you will have the 15-minutes video and 20 exercises to test your knowledge at the end of the database. Good luck!} *

