1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 (3... Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1 Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bf1 Nxe5 {This is, by far, Black's most common continuation.} (7... O-O 8. d4 Nf5 {Black plays this variation when he wants to keep more pieces on the board.} 9. Nf3 $1 {White's only continuation that fights for an advantage.} d5 10. Nc3 {[%csl Ge1,Rf5] We have a symmetrical structure where we are slightly ahead in development, and Black has a slightly misplaced knight on f5.} Bb4 {This is Black's most common continuation and also my favorite one.} (10... Nh4 {This is a standard move in the 8...Nf5 Berlin. Normally, Black would prefer to play Bd6 first so that after Nh4-Nxh4, he can recapture with the queen.} 11. Nxh4 Bxh4 12. Bb5 $5 {[%cal Gb5c6,Gc1f4,Gc3a4,Gd1d2,Ga4c5] This is my recommendation. We threat Bxc6, after which we can play an interesting structure.}) 11. a3 Ba5 {This is Black's standard continuation, and in my course "Berlin for Black" I mention a strong novelty for Whtie, which of course will be my recommendation in this occasion.} 12. Bg5 $14 {We provoke f6.} f6 13. Bf4 g5 {This is Black's critical continuation, and White's fantastic idea is} 14. Bc1 $1 {[%csl Gf6,Gg5][%cal Gb2b4,Gc3a4,Gc2c4] We lost two tempi (Bg5-Bf4) , but we provoked f6-g5, which are weakening Black's kingside.}) 8. Rxe5 O-O 9. d4 Bf6 {More than 3000 games have been played in this position, but we do not need to study all this big theory because we will play the very rare} 10. Re2 $5 {This move has been tried in only 150 games, but it completely changes the dynamics of the position compared to the big main line 10.Re1.} ({Why 10.Re2 is so much different than 10.Re1? This is the first logical question that we need to answer.} 10. Re1 {Black's main move is now} Re8 {after which it is extremely difficult for White to find ideas.} 11. Bf4 {is a very critical direction, but Black is fine after} Rxe1 $1 12. Qxe1 Ne8 {[%cal Gd7d5] Black is ready for d5, and if we prevent it by playing} 13. Nc3 {Black can play} Bxd4 $1 {Where there are a lot of high-level games, but Black equalizes with concrete moves.}) 10... b6 {[%cal Gc8a6] This is Black's most common continuation.} (10... Re8 {As we have just seen, this is Black's most common continuation against 10.Re1, but is it so good also here?} 11. Bf4 Rxe2 12. Qxe2 Ne8 13. Nc3 {[%csl Ge2]} Bxd4 {[%csl Ge1,Ge2] Do you remember this position? We had exactly the same position in the 10.Re1 note, only that White's queen was on e1. Here, the difference is huge:} 14. Re1 $1 Nf6 15. Nd5 $18 {And White is winning. We have just seen the main idea of our 10.Re2!?: the standard continuation 10...Re8 is not as good now as it was before. That's why Black usually tries to play something else.}) (10... Nf5 11. d5 $5 {Black's position is slightly uncomfortable.} d6 12. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2e4] Our idea is Ne4.} (12. Nc3 {Is not a good move now, because after} Bxc3 $1 13. bxc3 b6 $13 {Black's structure is very solid, and it's difficult for us to activate our bishops.})) (10... Nc4 {Kramnik's idea.} 11. b3 $1 {We force Black's knight to retreat on b6.} Nb6 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Gd7d5] Black will eventually play d7-d5, but the knight on b6 is not well placed.} 12. h3 $5 {[%csl Rb6,Rc8] This rare move is my recommendation. What is our idea? To play against Black's bishop on c8. We have a symmetrical position, but Black's knight on b6 is not great, and if Black starts to have problems also with the light-squares bishop, then it might be our chance to fight for an advantage.} d5 {This is Black's most logical move, and now we play} 13. Qd3 $1 {[%csl Rc8,Rf5,Rg4][%cal Gd3f5,Gh3g4,Rc8g4,Rc8f5] We play against Black's bishop c8.} Re8 14. Rxe8+ Qxe8 15. a4 a5 16. Bf4 c6 17. Nd2 $14 {[%csl Rb6,Gf3][%cal Gd2f3,Ga1e1,Gf3e5] Nf3-Re1 next, and our pieces are more active. Is it enough to win the game? It is difficult to say, but Black's position is unpleasant, and he needs to find good moves not to get worse.}) 11. Re1 $1 {We lost a tempo, but provoked the move b7-b6. How does it affect the game after the standard Re8?} Bb7 (11... Re8 {[%csl Gb6] We are playing the main position, but Black has included b6, which is not always good for him:} 12. Bf4 Rxe1 13. Qxe1 Qe7 {This is Black's most common continuation, and it was played in the Carlsen-Karjakin, WC 2016.} (13... Ne8 {[%cal Rf6d4,Ge1e4] In this position, when Black's pawn is still on b7, Bxd4 is a threat, but here, it's not possible because of the Qe4 idea. We can use this detail in our favor.} 14. Nc3 {Black cannot now play Bxd4 because of Qe4.} Bb7 15. Qd2 {[%cal Gd4d5] We prepare d5.} d5 {Black prevents d5, but he has to play with a bad bishop on b7. Black's position is very solid, but we can play claiming that the bishop on b7 is misplaced.} ({if Black plays a useful move like} 15... g6 {then after} 16. d5 $14 {We have achieved something.}) 16. Re1 {[%csl Rb7,Rd5][%cal Gg2g3,Gh2h4,Gc3d1,Gd1e3] White can continue with g3-h4, Nd1-Ne3. It's impossible to analyze all Black's moves, but we have some play.}) 14. Na3 $14 {[%cal Gc2c3] This is my novelty. Compared to 14.Nc3, we keep the c3 option to defend the d4 pawn.} (14. Nc3 {was played by Karjakin, but after} Bb7 15. Qxe7 Bxe7 $11 {Black was fine.}) 14... Bb7 15. c3 {Even the engine shows a +0,30 evaluation, which is already something. Of course, Black can play a lot of moves in this kind of positions, but I will show you our key ideas.} a6 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Ga6b5] Black covers the b5 square.} (15... Re8 $6 {Looks very natural, but suddenly after} 16. Qxe7 Bxe7 17. Bxd6 Bxd6 18. Nb5 $14 {Black has some problems.}) 16. Nc2 $1 {[%cal Ga8e8] The key aspect of the position is that Black cannot play Re8.} Re8 $2 17. Bxd6 $1 Qxe1 18. Rxe1 Rxe1 19. Nxe1 cxd6 20. g3 $16 {[%cal Gf1g2]}) 12. Bf4 {[%cal Gf4d6] We want to play Bxd6, and Black now has two possible continuations: Ne4 or Nf5.} Nf5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gf8e8,Rf5d4] Not all players are happy with the positions arising after 12...Ne4, because they may think that Black has to play precisely, and White keeps a small practical edge. By playing Nf5, Black gains a tempo against our d4 pawn and is ready to continue with Re8.} (12... Ne4 13. Nd2 {Very likely, we will have a position without knights where we have a small pressure.} Nxd2 {This is Black's most simple move.} 14. Qxd2 d6 {[%csl Gb7] Black keeps active his bishop, and the pawn on c7 will not be hanging now.} (14... d5 $6 {is not good because we can take control of the 'e' file:} 15. Re3 $1 Qd7 (15... Re8 $2 {[%csl Rc7] is not possible because of} 16. Rxe8+ Qxe8 17. Bxc7 $18) 16. Rae1 $16 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gf4e5] We can continue with Be5, and we have a serious advantage thanks to the control of the 'e' file.}) 15. a4 $1 {[%cal Ga4a5] We are ready to put pressure on the queenside by playing a5.} (15. Re3 {Was interesting against 14...d5, but here Black can just play} Re8 $11)) 13. c3 Re8 14. Nd2 g6 {Brkic-Robson, 2024.} 15. Rxe8+ Qxe8 16. a4 $14 {[%csl Rb6,Rb7,Rd7][%cal Ga4a5,Rd7d5,Rc8e6] White keeps the typical small pressure of this line.}) 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 {This is the Classical Spanish. It's an opening that has been played in more than 200.000 games!} (5... Nxe4 6. Re1 $5 {Our recommendation. The idea is to get a slightly more pleasant and playable position without the need to study all the big theory that arises after 5.d4.} Nc5 $1 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Gc5a4] This is Black's only good continuation.} 7. Bxc6 (7. Nxe5 $6 Nxe5 8. Rxe5+ Be7 $15 {[%csl Ra4] Black is already slightly better because he will manage to exchange our bishop on a4 and will have then the pair of bishops in a symmetrical position.}) 7... dxc6 8. Nxe5 {From the strategic point of view, Black is doing great because he has a solid structure and a pair of bishops, but we will try to use our lead in development to create problems. Now, Black's main move is 8...Be7 and we will consider it in the next chapter. Now, let's focus on the two sidelines: Ne6 and Be6.} Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8] This is Black's most common and solid continuation because Black is ready to castle in the next moves.} 9. d4 Ne6 {The knight on e6 is not well placed, but at least Black closes the 'e' file and is ready to castle on the next move.} 10. Be3 $1 {[%cal Gc2c4] This is our idea. We defend the d4 pawn and want to continue with c4.} (10. c3 {Is White's most common continuation, but after} O-O $13 {Black's position is solid and playable, and it's difficult for us to find interesting ideas.}) 10... O-O 11. c4 {[%csl Rc8,Re6][%cal Gb1c3,Rc8e6] Let's discuss this position. Black has two bishops and a solid position. On the other hand, we have more space in the center and easier development, and we play against the fact that Black's knight on e6 is misplaced as it makes passive also the bishop on c8.} f6 $1 {In my opinion, Black has to play this move sooner or later, so it makes sense to play it immediately.} (11... Bf6 $6 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Rf7f6] This may seem like a very natural move, and it has been played by many strong players, including Mamedyarov, but the bishop on f6 is misplaced because Black loses the important resource f7-f6.} 12. f4 $1 {Our knight is very stable on e5, and it will be hard for Black to complete the development.}) (11... Bd6 {The problem of this move is that White can play} 12. f4 {and when Black plays f6,} f6 13. Nd3 $1 {[%csl Rd4,Rd6][%cal Yd8d4] Is possible, because the d4 pawn is not hanging. Let's follow the high-level game Ragger-Bjerre, 2024.}) 12. Nf3 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gd1b3,Ga1d1,Yd4d5] What is our idea? Nc3-Qb3-Rad1, eventually d5. It's not easy for Black to generate a counterplay because he still needs to finish the development.} f5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gf5f4,Ge7f6] This is, by far, Black's most common continuation in practice and it has been played in the 70% of the games that reached this position. It's a very human move because Black wants to continue with f4-Bf4, putting some pressure against our d4 pawn. From a psychological point of view, it's normal that Black doesn't want to play a passive position and wants to start an active counterplay, but objectively, it may not be Black's best continuation.} (12... Re8 {[%cal Ge6f8] This is Black's most solid continuation. The idea is to remove the knight from the bad e6 square by playing Nf8.} 13. Nc3 $14 {[%cal Gd1b3,Gh2h3,Ga1d1,Gd4d5]}) 13. Bd2 $5 {[%cal Gd2c3] My idea is to immediately play Bc3.} Bf6 (13... Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Qxd4 15. Rxe7) 14. Bc3 {Black can play many moves, but the feeling is that it's much easier to play from the White side.}) 6. d3 $5 {This is our recommendation. Compared to the big main line 6.Re1, here there are much less games, and it's easier to find new ideas to pose problems to the opponent. I want to point out that we play 6.d3 only after Black has played 5...Be7. If we start with 5.d3 (Instead of 5.00) , then Black can develop his bishop on c5, and we don't want to play with d3 against Bc5 systems.} b5 (6... d6 {is a less common move order, but it's also possible. Our recommendation will be} 7. c4 $5 {And we will analyze it in Chapter 11.} O-O 8. h3 {[%cal Rc8g4] We prevent Bg4.} Be6 (8... Nd7 {The Nd7-Nc5 plan is standard in this structure.} 9. Nc3 Nc5 10. Bxc6 $1 bxc6 11. d4 $14) 9. Nc3 Nd7 {[%cal Gf7f5] This time, Black doesn't play for Nc5 but for f7-f5.} 10. Be3 f5 11. exf5 Bxf5 12. d4 $14 {Black can now choose if to allow d5 or if to take on d4.}) 7. Bb3 d6 8. a3 $1 {[%cal Rc6a5,Gb3a2] Important move so that after 8...Na5, we have the a2 square for our bishop.} O-O 9. Nc3 {This is our main position in the Classical Spanish.} Bg4 {This is Black's most common continuation, and the arising positions are very atypical for the Spanish. By immediately pinning the knight, he aims for a quick Nd4 idea.} (9... Nb8 {In the Breyer spirit.} 10. a4 $5 {This is White's most concrete try and also my recommendation.} b4 11. Nd5 Nxd5 12. Bxd5 c6 {Now, we have three possible moves: Bc4, Bb3, and Ba2. They all look the same, but there are important differences.} 13. Bc4 $14 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Rb8d7,Rd7c5,Yc8a6] This is my recommendation. My idea is to fight against both Nc5 and a5-Ba6 ideas.} a5 $1 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Yc8a6,Gc4a6,Ra4a5] This is Black's most principled continuation because he does not allow us to play a4-a5, but now our bishop is well placed on a6 because it challenges Black's Ba6 typical structural idea.} (13... d5 $6 {Black gains a tempo against our bishop, but this move only weakens his position:} 14. Bb3 $14 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf1e1,Gf3e5,Ye1e5] For example:}) (13... Nd7 14. a5 $1 {When we play a5, our position is usually slightly better:}) 14. Be3 {[%cal Gd3d4] We prepare d4.} (14. d4 d5 $11 {Black is in time to equalize.}) 14... d5 {This looks critical.} ({if Black plays a normal move like} 14... Nd7 {then after} 15. d4 {we have a slightly better position. For example:}) 15. Bb3) (9... Be6 10. Nd5 $1 {This move stops both Black's ideas, and in addition, Black cannot now capture on d5 with the knight. GM Baadur Jobava: 'transposes in Chapter 4.'} Nd4 {This is Black's principled continuation.} (10... Na5 {This move mixes the 9...Be6 variation with the 9...Na5 one. I think that White gets a pleasant edge after} 11. Nxf6+ Bxf6 12. Bxe6 fxe6 13. b4 $1 Nc6 14. c3 $14 {[%cal Gg2g3,Gg1g2,Gc1e3,Gd1e2,Gh2h4,Gf3h2,Ga1a2,Gf1a1,Ga3a4] We can improve our pieces by playing Be3-Qe2. Then we can consider an idea like Nd2 (or h4-Nh2) , followed by Qg4. White's position is slightly better and we can play a long game where Black needs to accurately defend. In practice, White scored 70%, which shows how unpleasant it is to play from the Black's side. Let's check two model games.}) 11. Nxd4 exd4 12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 13. Bxe6 fxe6 {[%csl Gc1,Rf6]} 14. Qg4 {[%cal Gc7c6,Gc6c5,Gc5c4,Ya8c8,Gh2h4,Gc1g5,Yh4h5,Yh5h6,Yf2f4] White gets a risk-free position, but Black is solid. White's main ideas are f4 or h4, followed by h5-h6 or by Bg5. Black's main plan is to play c5-c4 and generate a counterplay on the 'c' file. Of course, we cannot check all Black's possible moves because every move is possible in these positions, but it's important to understand the ideas.} Qd7 {[%csl Ga4,Gb3,Gc2,Gd3][%cal Gc7c5,Gc5c4,Gb2b3,Ga3a4]}) (9... Na5 {In the Chigorin spirit.} 10. Ba2 Be6 {Compared to the previous chapter 9...Be6, White shouldn't now play Nd5 because Nxd5 will be possible.} (10... c5 {Black plays in Chigorin style, but it doesn't work great here:} 11. b4 Nc6 {[%csl Gb4]} 12. Nd5 $1 {Same idea as in the 11...cxb4 12.axb4 Nc6 variation.} Be6 (12... a5 {Was recently tried by Sindarov, but White is better after} 13. c4 $1) 13. Nxf6+ $5 Bxf6 14. Bxe6 fxe6 15. bxc5 dxc5 16. Be3 Nd4 17. Nd2 $14 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Gc2c3,Ya3a4,Gd1b3,Gb3e6,Gd1e2,Gf1b1] We can continue with a4 or c3, and we have a non-standard where it might be difficult to play from the Black's side.}) 11. Bg5 $5 {This is White's most interesting continuation, in my opinion.} c5 $1 {This is Black's strongest continuation. Compared to 10...c5, now our plan b4-Nc6-Nd5 is less strong.} (11... Bxa2 12. Rxa2 Nc6 {Black decides to retreat his knight to a good square, but after} (12... c5 $6 {This is a strategic mistake because Black weakens the d5 square:} 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. b4 Nc6 15. Nd5 $14 {White has a serious positional plus.}) (12... c6 {Black prevents Nd5, but after} 13. b4 {[%csl Ra5] The knight must retreat to the passive b7 square.} Nb7 {[%csl Rb7]} 14. d4) 13. a4 $1 b4 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Nd5 a5 16. c3 $14 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Rc6d4] Black was not in time to play Nd4, which means that our knight on d5 will stay there for some time.}) 12. Bxf6 {By playing this typical exchange, we get access to the d5 square. The only question will be " Is it enough to get an advantage ?"} Bxf6 13. Nd5 {Black now has two main plans: g6-Bg7, or Nc6, followed by a5 and some queenside play.} Nc6 14. a4 $1 {This is a very important detail: we do not allow Black to place his pawns on b4 and a5, as in the 14.c3 variation.} (14. c3 {is White's most common continuation, but Black can now play} a5 $1 {[%cal Ga5a4] With the idea a4, and if we play} 15. a4 {He is in time to play} b4 $13 {And he gets a good queenside counterplay, and the position is just equal.}) 14... b4 {This is Black's most common continuation, but we can now play} 15. a5 $1 {[%cal Ga6a5]} g6 $1 {Black's most logical continuation, with the idea to improve the bishop on g7.} (15... Nxa5 $2 {Would be a serious mistake because of} 16. Nxf6+ gxf6 17. Bd5 Bxd5 18. exd5 $16 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gf3h4,Gh4f5] Nh4-Nf5 next, and White has a good advantage.}) 16. c3 $14) (9... Bb7 {In the Zaitsev spirit.} 10. Re1 {[%cal Yh2h3] We play the typical useful move Re1, waiting to see which plan chooses Black. Eventually, we can play another waiting move - h3. Normally, Black has three main ideas: Na5, in the Chigorin spirit; Nb8, in the Breyer spirit; and the Qd7-Nd8-Ne6 popular plan.} Qd7 {[%cal Gc6d8,Gd8e6] Black's plan is Nd8-Ne6.} 11. h3 {we play another useful waiting move.} Rfe8 $1 {Black also slowly improves his position without committing too early for a certain plan.} (11... Nd8 $6 {is premature because of} 12. d4 $14) 12. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5f6,Gc3d5] Our idea is to take on f6 and play Nd5.} Nd8 {Black executes his typical idea Nd8-Ne6. As a rule, whenever Black plays Nd8, we must play d4!} (12... h6 {Black doesn't believe in our plan and is ready to play the position after Bxf6-Bxf6-Nd5.} 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Nd5 {[%cal Yf6e7,Ye7d8] Black tried Be7 and Bd8.} Bd8 15. Ne3 {[%cal Ge3f5] Sometimes, we might play Nf5.} Ne7 {Black covers the important d5 and f5 squares, but allows us to start a kingside play with} 16. Nh4 (16. h4 $5) 16... Rf8 {only move.} 17. Qf3 $36 {[%csl Rb7,Rc8,Rd7] I am sure that if you play the Spanish, you like these positions!}) 13. d4 $1 exd4 14. Nxd4 h6 (14... Nxe4 $4 {Is a big mistake, but it's important to mention it:} 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 16. Rxe4 Bxg5 {and White is winning only after} 17. Qg4 $18 {as happened in the game Svidler-Almasi, 2003.}) 15. Bf4 $14 {[%csl Gf4] If you have studied my course about the Philidor, you will for sure know that in this structure (White's pawn on e4 vs Black's pawn on d6) , the best square for the bishop is exactly f4.}) 10. Be3 {[%cal Ge3d4] We have to play this move to take control of the important d4 square.} Nd4 {This is Black's critical and most principled continuation. It has been played in more than 600 games.} 11. Bxd4 exd4 12. Nd5 {After White plays h3, Black will be compelled to capture on f3; retreating the bishop would leave the d4 pawn undefended. Once Black exchanges his bishop for our knight on f3, we can proceed by trading the remaining pair of knights, achieving an optimal setup: a position with opposite-colored bishops, where our bishop stands significantly stronger.} Nxd5 {Is Aronian's favorite move.} (12... h6 {Let's better illustrate the concept by seeing what happens if Black plays a waiting move.} 13. h3 {we continue with our planned move. Black's bishop cannot retreat on d7 because the d4 pawn would be hanging, and it cannot go to h5 because of g4, so} Bxf3 {is forced. We can now exchange the knights with check} 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. Qxf3 $14 {[%csl Gb3,Rf6][%cal Ga3a4] And we have our ideal set-up: an opposite-color bishop position. It is evident that our bishop is much more active than Black's one. Our idea is to play a4, and eventually, we can even fight for the 'a' line if our opponent allows us to play Bd5.}) (12... Nd7 $5 {[%csl Gb3,Gd7] By playing this move, Black's idea is to achieve a position with a knight on d7 against our bishop on b3.} 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 c6 15. Nxe7+ Qxe7 {Our bishop on b3 is very strong, but Black hopes to deal with his activity, and one day, his knight might not be worse than our bishop.} 16. Qg3 $14 {[%csl Gb2,Gb3,Yd7,Rf6][%cal Gf2f4,Gd7c5,Gc5a4,Ga4b2,Ga1b1] Our idea is f4.}) (12... c6 {This is a tricky move, and it's extremely important for White to know the right reaction.} 13. h3 $1 {This is an extremely important move order.} (13. Nxf6+ $6 {Would be a mistake, because after} Bxf6 14. h3 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gf6d4] Black's bishop can now retreat, as the d4 pawn is not hanging.} Bd7 $13 {Black is immediately fine.}) 13... Bxf3 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. Qxf3 $14 {[%cal Ga3a4] We achieve our ideal opposite-color bishops' position, which we have already discussed in the 12...h6 variation.}) (12... c5 {[%csl Rd5] Is Ding's favorite move. By playing c5, Black defends the d4 pawn and ensures that in the case of h3, his bishop on g4 can retreat because the d4 pawn is no longer hanging. The obvious drawback of this move is that the d5 square is now very weak.} 13. a4 {[%csl Re7][%cal Ga4b5,Ga6b5,Ya1a8,Yd8a8,Rd5e7] We have a huge threat: axb5-axb5-Rxa8-Qxa8-Nxe7+.} Be6 $1 {Black's only move.} (13... Rc8 14. axb5 axb5 15. Ra7 $16 {[%csl Ga7][%cal Ga7h7]}) 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. Bxe6 fxe6 {This position has been played a lot of times by Ding Liren.} 16. Qe2 $14 {[%csl Gf3,Rf6,Gg2][%cal Ge4e5,Gg2g3,Gg1g2,Gh2h4,Gf3h2,Gh2g4,Ge2g4] This is a useful move. For example, sometimes we might think about e4-e5.}) 13. Bxd5 {Black now tries Rb8 or Rc8.} Rc8 {[%cal Gc7c6] Black immediately prepares c6.} 14. Bc6 $5 {This is, in my opinion, White's most promising continuation. It looks artificial, but it's very important for us to stop c7-c6.} Bf6 {[%csl Gd4,Yg4][%cal Gf6d4,Yg4e6,Yg4d7] This is Black's most common and logical move because he defends the d4 pawn, and the bishop on g4 is flexible now.} (14... Bd7 $2 {Would be a serious mistake, because after} 15. Bxd7 Qxd7 16. Nxd4) 15. a4 $1 {We use this time to open the 'a' file.} Rb8 {[%cal Gb8b6,Yc7c6,Yc6d5] This is Aronian's latest try. Black prepares Rb6-Bd5-c6.} (15... b4 $2 {Would be a serious mistake, because White can now play} 16. Bb7 Rb8 17. Bxa6 $16 {[%cal Ga6c4] And the bishop can safely retreat on c4.}) (15... Bd7 {This was Aronian's first idea, but then he changed in favor of 15...Rb8, which means that 15...Bd7 was at least not fully equalizing.} 16. Bxd7 Qxd7 17. b3 $5 {This is a very useful move for us.} (17. Qd2 $6 {[%csl Rd2][%cal Rf3d2] Was played by many strong players, but I don't like this move because we need to keep free the d2 square for our knight.}) 17... c5 18. Nd2 $1 {[%csl Gd2] Our knight is well placed on d2, because it is prepared for Black's main idea d6-d5.}) 16. h3 {We immediately force Black to take a decision. Now, all the three bishop's moves are possible.} Be6 {This move was played by Aronian against Caruana in 2017.} (16... Bd7 {is the most simple one for us, because after} 17. Bxd7 Qxd7 18. b3 $14 {[%csl Gf3,Rf6] We have a typical position where our knight is more useful than Black's bishop on f6.}) 17. axb5 axb5 18. Re1 $14 {This is my recommendation. We play this useful waiting move, and if Black plays in Aronian's style:} Rb6 19. Bd5 Bxd5 20. exd5 b4 {[%csl Ge1][%cal Gd1d2] We have now the d2 square for our knight.} 21. Nd2 $14 {[%cal Gd1f3,Gd2c4,Ga1a5]} *

