1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 {This is the Classical Spanish. It's an opening that has been played in more than 200.000 games!} 6. d3 $5 {This is our recommendation. Compared to the big main line 6.Re1, here there are much less games, and it's easier to find new ideas to pose problems to the opponent. I want to point out that we play 6.d3 only after Black has played 5...Be7. If we start with 5.d3 (Instead of 5.00) , then Black can develop his bishop on c5, and we don't want to play with d3 against Bc5 systems.} (6. Re1 {Is White's big main line, but it has some practical and theoretical problems.} b5 7. Bb3 {Black can now choose between} O-O {Even if you invest a huge amount of time in understanding and learning all the 7...d6 lines, you also need to find an idea against the Marshall.} (7... d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 {Which is the classical variation, and now Black has a lot of very important lines. White can get a game against most of them, but to well-understand the positions it requires a life time!} Bb7 (9... Nb8 {Breyer defence, more than 20.000 games.}) (9... Na5 {Chigorin defence, more than 40.000 games.}) 10. d4 Re8 {Zaitsev defence, more than 20.000 games. These 3 options, are only Black's most common continuations, but other moves are also possible!}) 8. c3 (8. a4 {White can try some Anti-Marshall system, like 8.a4, but even here there are more than 10.000 games, and it's extremely difficult to find new ideas.}) 8... d5 {[%eval 2000,0] games, and nowadays, it's getting almost impossible to find ideas to fight for something with White.}) 6... b5 (6... d6 {is a less common move order, but it's also possible. Our recommendation will be} 7. c4 $5 {And we will analyze it in Chapter 11.}) 7. Bb3 d6 8. a3 $1 {[%cal Rc6a5,Gb3a2] Important move so that after 8...Na5, we have the a2 square for our bishop. Now, Black's most common continuation is 8...00, but we will analyze the sidelines in Chapter 10.} O-O 9. Nc3 {This is our main position in the Classical Spanish. Black has a lot of possible continuations, and we will analyze all of them separately. Compared to the big numbers of the mainline 6.Re1, here there are only 2000 games, which is a much more human number!} Bb7 {In the Zaitsev spirit, will be analyzed in Chapter 2.} (9... Nb8 {In the Breyer spirit, will be analyzed in Chapter 3.}) (9... Be6 {Will be analyzed in Chapter 4.}) (9... Na5 {In the Chigorin spirit, will be analyzed in Chapter 5.}) (9... Bg4 {This is Black's most common continuation, and the arising positions are very atypical for the Spanish. We will analyze it in Chapters 7-8-9.}) (9... Rb8 $5 {It is a very popular move nowadays in high-level games, and we will analyze it in Chapter 6 together with 9...h6.}) *

