1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. d3 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. a3 O-O 9. Nc3 Bb7 {By playing this move, Black goes against the old principle that was saying, "When White puts the pawn on d3, Black shouldn't develop the bishop on b7". Having said this, the move is still very playable for Black.} 10. Re1 {[%cal Yh2h3] We play the typical useful move Re1, waiting to see which plan chooses Black. Eventually, we can play another waiting move - h3. Normally, Black has three main ideas: Na5, in the Chigorin spirit; Nb8, in the Breyer spirit; and the Qd7-Nd8-Ne6 popular plan.} Qd7 {[%cal Gc6d8,Gd8e6] Black's plan is Nd8-Ne6.} (10... Na5 11. Ba2 c5 {We have many possible continuations, but I like} 12. b4 $5 Nc6 13. Rb1 {Usually, White is preferable in this structure. For example:} Qc7 {Now, we have two interesting directions:} (13... Nd4 14. bxc5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Rd6c5,Gf3e5] Using the fact that Black cannot retake dxc5 because of Nxe5.} Nxf3+ 15. Qxf3 dxc5 16. Qg3 {[%cal Gg3e5] We attack the pawn on e5, and after} Qd6 {we can maneuver our knight:} 17. Nd1 $14 {[%cal Gd1e3,Gc1b2,Ye1f1,Yf2f4,Ya3a4] We can continue with Ne3-Bb2, and then we can play a4 or Rf1-f4.}) 14. bxc5 (14. Nd5 $14 Nxd5 15. exd5 Nd4 16. c4 $13 {It is a very complicated new position, in which it seems that Black should play accurately to equalize.}) 14... dxc5 15. Bg5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gc3d5] We are fighting for the d5 square, for example:} Nd4 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Nd5 Qd6 18. Nxd4 cxd4 19. a4 $1 Bc6 20. axb5 axb5 21. Bb3 $14 {[%cal Ge1f1,Gf2f4] We can play for Rf1-f4. Black's position is solid, but White has better chances.}) (10... Nb8 {Black plays in a sort of Breyer spirit.} 11. Ne2 Nbd7 12. Ng3 Re8 $1 {[%cal Ge7f8,Gh7h6,Gd6d5] Black's critical continuation. The idea is to slowly prepare d5 with the moves h6-Bf8.} (12... Nc5 {This is Black's most common continuation, but after} 13. Ba2 {[%cal Ga2g8,Gg3f5,Gf3g5] White is better because all the pieces are ready for a kingside attack.} Ne6 14. Nf5 Re8 {White can now choose between two options:} 15. Bxe6 {Positional way.} (15. Ng5 $36 {Aggressive way.}) 15... fxe6 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 17. b4 $14 {[%csl Rb7] White can play a long and slightly better game, mainly because the bishop on b7 is a bad piece.}) (12... h6 $2 {Is a bad move because of} 13. Nf5 Re8 14. Bxh6 $18 {and Black is already lost.}) 13. Ng5 d5 $1 14. exd5 Bxd5 {This critical position has been played only in the Vokhidov-Duda, 2022 game. White played Bxd5, but I will offer an interesting novelty:} 15. c4 $14 bxc4 16. dxc4 Bc6 17. c5 Rf8 18. Nf5 Nxc5 19. Ba2 $1 {This position is very hard for Black. Now, the only move is} h6 $1 {White can now choose between two continuations:} 20. Nf3 {This is the most solid option, after which Black must find} (20. b4 $5 {This is a more aggressive idea.} hxg5 21. bxc5 Re8 22. Qc2 $36 {[%cal Gf5h6,Gc2g6] This is a very interesting position, which the engine evaluates +0,10. It's clear that White has a big initiative for the sacrificed pawn, but Black can probably equalize with a good defense. For example, Nh6+ gxh6 - Qg6+ is already a big threat.}) 20... Be4 $1 21. Nxe5 Bxf5 22. Nc6 Qxd1 23. Nxe7+ Kh8 24. Rxd1 Bc2 $1 25. Re1 Nb3 26. Bxb3 Bxb3 27. Bd2 $14 {Still, White is slightly better in this endgame.}) 11. h3 {we play another useful waiting move.} Rfe8 $1 {Black also slowly improves his position without committing too early for a certain plan.} (11... Nd8 $6 {is premature because of} 12. d4 $1 exd4 13. Nxd4 Re8 (13... c5 $2 14. Nf5 c4 15. Ba2 Re8 16. Bg5 $16 {[%cal Yb2b3] White has a big advantage. Eventually, we can consider playing b3 to activate our bishop.}) 14. Nf5 Ne6 (14... Bf8 $2 15. Bg5 $18 {Black was already lost in Shirov-Anand, 2004.}) 15. Bd2 $14 {It's very difficult to understand why, but this is White's best move according to the engine. My explanation is that White should play another useful move, waiting to see Black's plan. For example:} ({If you feel that 15.Bd2 is too deep, you can always play} 15. Nxe7+ Rxe7 16. f3 $14 {which is good enough for a long-term advantage.}) 15... Bf8 (15... c5 16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. exd5 Nd4 18. Nxd4 cxd4 19. a4 $14) 16. Qf3 $14 {Very unpleasant position for Black.}) (11... Rae8 $6 {Black's rook on a8 is useful. Now, White can play on the queenside:} 12. a4 b4 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Na5 15. Bxb7 Nxb7 16. d4 $14 {[%csl Ra6] Sometimes, in the future, the pawn on a6 could be hanging.}) 12. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5f6,Gc3d5] Our idea is to take on f6 and play Nd5.} (12. Bd2 $5 {is also an interesting possibility. We play another useful move, and sooner or later, Black will need to make a choice.}) 12... Nd8 {Black executes his typical idea Nd8-Ne6. As a rule, whenever Black plays Nd8, we must play d4!} (12... h6 {Black doesn't believe in our plan and is ready to play the position after Bxf6-Bxf6-Nd5.} 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Nd5 {[%cal Yf6e7,Ye7d8] Black tried Be7 and Bd8.} Bd8 (14... Be7 {Looks more strange compared to 14...Bd8, but it was played in the game Inarkiev-Leko, 2009.} 15. c4 $5 {This is my recommendation, and we aim to get a less standard position.} (15. c3 $14 {[%cal Gd3d4] is also a possible direction, with the idea d4, and White keeps better chances.}) 15... Na5 $1 {This is probably Black's best continuation.} (15... Bf8 16. Rc1 {[%cal Gc4b5,Ga6b5,Ya3a4] our idea is cxb5-axb5-a4.} Ne7 {is Black's most logical move.} (16... Rac8 17. cxb5 axb5 18. a4 Ne7 19. axb5 Nxd5 20. exd5 $14 {[%cal Rd7b5,Gb3a4] Black cannot capture on b5 because of Ba4.}) 17. cxb5 Nxd5 18. bxa6 Rxa6 19. exd5 Ra5 20. Qc2 Bxd5 21. Bxd5 Rxd5 22. b4 $14 {White is at least slightly better.}) (15... Nd4 16. Nxd4 exd4 17. cxb5 axb5 18. a4 $14) 16. Ba2 {[%cal Gb2b4] We are ready for b4, so Black must act concretely.} Bxd5 17. cxd5 c5 $1 {only move, otherwise we play b4 and we have a much better position.} (17... Rec8 $2 18. b4 Nb7 {[%csl Rb7]} 19. d4 $16 {[%csl Rb7] We have a big advantage because Black's knight on b7 is very passive.}) 18. dxc6 Nxc6 19. Bd5 $14 {[%cal Gd3d4] We are strategically better because our bishop is much stronger, and we also have d4 ideas.} Bd8 {[%cal Gd8b6] Black also wants to activate his bishop on b6.} (19... Bf8 20. d4 $14) (19... Rac8 {This move is against d4, but now we can play} 20. a4 $16 (20. d4 $6 exd4 21. Nxd4 Nxd4 {Black can take because the rook is no longer on a8.} 22. Qxd4 Bf6 $11 {Obviously, Black is doing very fine.})) 20. a4 Bb6 21. Nh4 $36 {[%cal Gh4f5,Gd1h5,Yd1g4] We have great prospects on the kingside.}) 15. Ne3 {[%cal Ge3f5] Sometimes, we might play Nf5.} Be7 {Was played in the game Grischuk-Inarkiev, 2008. Now, I like the following continuation:} (15... Ne7 {Black covers the important d5 and f5 squares, but allows us to start a kingside play with} 16. Nh4 (16. h4 $5) 16... Rf8 {only move.} 17. Qf3 $36 {I am sure that if you play the Spanish, you like these positions!}) 16. Nf5 Bf8 17. N3h4 $5 {We immediately start an initiative on the kingside. Of course, I can stop here, but I will show you some extra lines to make you understand some typical attacking ideas.} Kh7 {[%cal Gg7g6] A standard move that prepares g6.} 18. Qg4 $1 Rad8 {[%csl Gd7][%cal Gd8d7,Yg7g6] Black defends his queen and is now ready for g6.} (18... g6 $2 {is not possible now because of} 19. Nxh6 $16 {And White gains material.}) 19. Nf3 $1 {[%cal Gf3g5] Ng5+ is already a big threat.} g6 ({For example, if Black just ignores our treat, we can win after} 19... a5 20. Ng5+ $1 hxg5 21. Qh5+ Kg8 22. Qg6 $18 {[%cal Gf5h6,Gh6f7] Nh6-Nxf7 is coming.}) 20. Qh4 f6 $1 {Only move, but now we can play against the g6 pawn:} (20... gxf5 $2 21. Ng5+ Kg7 22. Nxf7 $16 {is a disaster for Balck.}) 21. Ne3 {[%cal Gh4f6]} Bg7 {again, only move.} 22. a4 {First, we can try to open the 'a' file.} Na5 (22... b4 23. a5 $14 {We have initiative on the kingside but also a better structure on the queenside.}) 23. Ba2 b4 24. Qg3 $36 {[%cal Gf3h4] Nh4 next, and Black still needs to play very well.}) 13. d4 $1 exd4 14. Nxd4 h6 (14... Nxe4 $4 {Is a big mistake, but it's important to mention it:} 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 16. Rxe4 Bxg5 {and White is winning only after} 17. Qg4 $18 {as happened in the game Svidler-Almasi, 2003.}) 15. Bf4 $1 {[%csl Gf4] If you have studied my course about the Philidor, you will for sure know that in this structure (White's pawn on e4 vs Black's pawn on d6) , the best square for the bishop is exactly f4.} Ne6 {A very logical move.} (15... c5 {[%csl Re4] Natural, active move. Black wants to win the pawn on e4 concretely.} 16. Nf5 {The variation will be extremely forced now:} c4 17. Ba2 Bxe4 (17... Nxe4 $4 18. Qg4 $18 {[%cal Gg4g7,Gf5h6]}) 18. Nxh6+ $1 gxh6 19. Nxe4 Nxe4 20. Rxe4 Qf5 21. Qe2 d5 22. Rxe7 Rxe7 23. Qxe7 Qxf4 {[%csl Rg8] The material is equal, and we can play against Black's weaker king. For example:} 24. Qe8+ (24. Re1 $5 Ne6 25. Re3 $13 {is another interesting direction.}) 24... Kg7 25. Rd1 Qd6 26. c3 $13 {[%csl Gg1,Rg7][%cal Ga2b1] We intend Bb1 next. According to the engine, the position is balanced, but I would prefer White in an OTB game.}) (15... Bf8 {This is Black's best continuation, according to the engine.} 16. Nd5 $1 Nxd5 17. exd5 {[%csl Rb7] The bishop on b7 is very bad, so Black has to play c5.} c5 18. dxc6 Nxc6 {Black accepts the structural damage because it is crucial for him to activate the bishop on b7.} 19. Nxc6 Rxe1+ (19... Qxc6 20. Qg4 $14) 20. Qxe1 Qxc6 21. Qf1 $14 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gf4e3,Rd6d5,Rd5d4] The engine evaluates only +0,15, but we can play a risk-free long game. Our next moves could be Rd1-Be3 to Block the 'd' pawn. If Black's pawn remains on d6, we might consider c2-c4 ideas with the idea to have a two vs. one majority on the queenside.}) 16. Nxe6 fxe6 17. Qd3 $1 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Ge4e5,Gd3g6] We are ready for e5, and our queen will have access to the important g6 square.} (17. e5 {unfortunately doesn't work because of} Qc6 $11) 17... c5 18. e5 $1 {We absolutely must go for it; otherwise, we will be worse.} Nh5 (18... c4 $14 19. exf6 $1 {an important tactical detail.} cxd3 (19... Bxf6 20. Bxc4 bxc4 21. Qxd6 $16 {positionally better for White.}) 20. Bxe6+ Qxe6 21. Rxe6 Bxf6 22. Rxe8+ Rxe8 23. cxd3 $14 {Black still needs to demonstrate the compensation for the missing pawn.}) 19. Be3 c4 20. Bxc4 $1 bxc4 21. Qg6 Qc6 $1 22. f3 {This is a critical position. Of course, if we are allowed to take on h5, our position will be better. Black needs to act quickly.} Bh4 $1 (22... d5 $6 23. Qxh5 Bc5 24. Nd1 $16) 23. Qxh5 Bxe1 24. Rxe1 d5 {Two correspondence games reached this position, but after} 25. Ne2 $14 {White has a huge compensation for the missing exchange. We have the important d4 square for our knight, and we can always play for the f4-f5 plan. Engine evaluates +0,40, but in a practical game, it's even more difficult to play from the Black side.} *

