1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. d3 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. a3 O-O 9. Nc3 Nb8 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gc8b7] Black goes for the Breyer plan: Nb8-Nd7. Compared to other more concrete moves like Na5 or Bg4, Black doesn't want to force things, but instead wants to build a solid position.} 10. a4 $5 {This is White's most concrete try and also my recommendation.} (10. Ne2 {Was played by Kramnik, but after} c5 (10... Nbd7 {is Black's most common continuation, but here White has a good game:} 11. Ng3 Nc5 12. Ba2 Be6 13. Bb1 $14 {[%cal Gc2c3,Gd3d4,Gf1e1] We can slowly prepare c3-d4.}) 11. Ng3 Nc6 12. c3 Be6 {Black has a good game, in my opinion. White can still try} 13. Bxe6 fxe6 14. b4 $13 {[%cal Yd8d7,Yd6d5] but Black can try different moves like Qd7-d5. The position is still playable, the engine evaluates +0,20, but it's about taste.}) (10. h3 {Is also playable, for example:} Nbd7 11. a4 b4 12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. Bxd5 Rb8 (13... Ra7 14. a5 $14) 14. d4 $14 {as happened in the game Yuffa-Salem, 2023.} (14. a5 Bb7 $11)) 10... b4 11. Nd5 Nxd5 12. Bxd5 c6 {Now, we have three possible moves: Bc4, Bb3, and Ba2. They all look the same, but there are important differences.} 13. Bc4 $14 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Rb8d7,Rd7c5,Yc8a6] This is my recommendation. My idea is to fight against both Nc5 and a5-Ba6 ideas.} (13. Bb3 {This is White's most common and logical move. Why don't we play it?} Nd7 14. a5 (14. Be3 {[%cal Rd7c5] is intended against Nc5. If we are able to play a5 on the next move, our position will be better, but Black is in time to play} a5 $11 {[%cal Gc8a6] Ba6 next, and the position is equal.}) 14... Nc5 $11 {[%csl Rb3] Black gets an important tempo against our bishop and is immediately fine.}) (13. Ba2 {This looks clever because, after Nd7-a5, Black can no longer gain a tempo against our bishop by playing Nc5.} a5 $14 (13... Nd7 14. a5 $14) 14. Be3 Nd7 15. d4 Ba6 $11 {Black's position is fine.}) 13... a5 $1 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Yc8a6,Gc4a6,Ra4a5] This is Black's most principled continuation because he does not allow us to play a4-a5, but now our bishop is well placed on a6 because it challenges Black's Ba6 typical structural idea.} (13... d5 $6 {Black gains a tempo against our bishop, but this move only weakens his position:} 14. Bb3 $14 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf1e1,Gf3e5,Ye1e5] For example:} Qd6 15. Re1 Nd7 16. exd5 cxd5 17. Nxe5 $1 Nxe5 18. Bf4 $16) (13... Nd7 14. a5 $1 {When we play a5, our position is usually slightly better:} Bb7 15. Re1 {[%cal Gd3d4] We are ready to play d4.} d5 $1 (15... Nf6 16. c3 bxc3 17. bxc3 $14) 16. Bb3 Qc7 17. c3 bxc3 18. bxc3 $14 {[%csl Rb7] We are just slightly better because it will be very difficult for Black to activate the bishop on b7. The engine evaluates +0,30, which is very difficult to get in the Classical Spanish!}) 14. Be3 {[%cal Gd3d4] We prepare d4.} (14. d4 d5 $11 {Black is in time to equalize.}) 14... d5 {This looks critical.} ({if Black plays a normal move like} 14... Nd7 {then after} 15. d4 {we have a slightly better position. For example:} Qc7 (15... exd4 16. Nxd4 Ne5 17. Be2 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gd1d2]}) 16. dxe5 dxe5 17. Qe2 $14 {[%cal Rc8a6] Black suffers because he cannot play his typical Ba6 idea.}) 15. Bb3 d4 {This is Black's critical continuation, according to the engine.} (15... Qd6 {allows} 16. d4 $1 exd4 17. Qxd4 {And White has the initiative and maybe the advantage.} Be6 18. exd5 cxd5 (18... Bxd5 $6 19. Bf4 $14 {[%cal Ga1d1]}) 19. Bf4 Qa6 20. Bg5 $14 {Looks unpleasant for Black.}) (15... Bf6 16. c3 bxc3 17. bxc3 Be6 18. Qc2 $14 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ye4d5,Yc6d5,Gc2a2,Gd3d4] /= Black's position is for sure playable, but he did not fully equalize. We might continue with Qa2 or exd5-exd5 Qa2, with some chances. Another plan could be d3-d4, which sometimes works in our favor.}) 16. Nxe5 $1 {This is the brilliant resource we have.} ({if we play the standard} 16. Bd2 {then Black is fine after} Nd7 $11 {[%cal Ge7d6,Gd7c5,Gc8e6] With the idea Bd6-Nc5-Be6.}) 16... dxe3 17. Nxf7 {The next moves are forced for both sides:} Rxf7 18. fxe3 Bf6 19. e5 {Now, Black has a choice.} Kh8 (19... Nd7 20. e6 Ne5 21. exf7+ Nxf7 22. Rf4 $36 {An engine may defend, but it looks very unpleasant for Black.}) 20. Bxf7 Bxe5 21. d4 Bf6 22. Qh5 $36 {It's very difficult for Black to defend in an OTB game. Even if we cannot maintain the initiative, we still have a very good material balance: rook and two pawns vs knight and bishop, which could be good for us, especially in endgames. CONCLUSIONS: In the 9...Nb8 variation, you have different interesting continuations: h3, Ne2, but my main recommendation is the concrete 9.a4. Thanks to our 13.Bc4!? novelty, White keeps good chances of creating pressure, and Black immediately needs to react correctly, which is not always easy.} *

