1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. d3 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. a3 O-O 9. Nc3 Be6 {[%cal Gd6d5,Ye6b3] Black immediately challenges our strong bishop on b3 and also prepares d6-d5.} 10. Nd5 $1 {This move stops both Black's ideas, and in addition, Black cannot now capture on d5 with the knight.} Nd4 {This is Black's principled continuation.} (10... Bxd5 {Black can capture on d5 with the bishop, but we will have the pair of bishops for free, and we can play a long and more pleasant game:} 11. exd5 Nd4 (11... Nb8 {[%cal Gb8d7] Black doesn't want to damage his structure, but after} 12. a4 Nbd7 13. d4 $14 {[%csl Gb3,Gc1] White obviously has an edge, thanks to the pair of bishops.}) 12. Nxd4 exd4 {[%cal Gf6d7,Gd7b6,Ge7f6] In this structure, Black's best set-up is probably Nd7-Nb6-Bf6.} 13. c3 $1 {we immediately force a structural change.} dxc3 ({Some players have tried} 13... Nd7 $6 {but after} 14. cxd4 Bf6 15. Be3 Nb6 16. Qf3 $16 {[%cal Gf1c1,Gc1c2,Ya1c1] Black doesn't have enough compensation for the missing pawn, and we can continue by doubling our rooks on the 'c' file.}) 14. bxc3 Nd7 15. g3 $14 {[%csl Gb3,Gc1][%cal Gh2h4] We want to take some space on the kingside by playing h4, and our position is obviously slightly better thanks to the pair of bishops.}) (10... Na5 {This move mixes the 9...Be6 variation with the 9...Na5 one. I think that White gets a pleasant edge after} 11. Nxf6+ Bxf6 12. Bxe6 fxe6 13. b4 $1 Nc6 (13... Nb7 $6 14. c4 $16 {[%csl Rb7] Black's knight on b7 is really bad.}) 14. c3 $14 {We can improve our pieces by playing Be3-Qe2. Then we can consider an idea like Nd2 (or h4-Nh2) , followed by Qg4. White's position is slightly better and we can play a long game where Black needs to accurately defend. In practice, White scored 70%, which shows how unpleasant it is to play from the Black's side. Let's check two model games.} Qd7 (14... Ne7 {[%cal Ge7g6] Black wants to transfer his knight on g6.} 15. Qb3 {Not White's best move, but it's also possible.} (15. Be3 $5 {would have been my choice.} Ng6 16. g3 $14 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gg1g2,Gd1e2] We can improve our position with Kg2-Qe2, and Black's knight on g6 is misplaced. I say that White is slightly better, but for the engine, this is already +0,70.}) 15... Qd7 16. a4 Ng6 17. g3 Be7 18. Kg2 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gc1e3] White improved his position and can continue with Be3-h4.} d5 $1 {Black, correctly, tries to create a counterplay.} 19. h4 dxe4 20. dxe4 Qd3 {The engine approves of Black's play, but from a practical point of view, the problem with such committing decisions is that later, you will need to find some only moves, which is not easy OTB.} 21. Qxe6+ Rf7 22. Ng5 Bxg5 23. Bxg5 {According to the engine Black is getting closer to equality compared to the position after 18.Kg2, but he needs to find the seemingly anti-positional} Qxe4+ $2 (23... bxa4 $3 {When White has only a +0,20 advantage, I don't want to dig into the consequences of this concrete position, but I want to make you understand that very often, Black has to choose if to passively wait or start a counterplay, which might be good but practically difficult to manage as it often requires to find many only moves.}) 24. f3 Qc4 25. Qxc4 bxc4 26. Rad1 $18 {Black's position is objectively lost. Kryvoruchko-Grigoryan, 2014.}) 15. a4 {I cannot say that the move is bad, but I wouldn't play it because it creates more tension between the pawns, and I feel that in some moments, it could be easier for Black to equalize concretely.} (15. Be3 {would have been my choice. For example:} Rfb8 16. Nd2 $14 {[%cal Gd1g4] Qg4 next, with a pleasant advantage.}) 15... Ne7 16. Be3 Ng6 (16... a5 $1 {Was Black's best choice.} 17. axb5 Qxb5 18. Rxa5 Rxa5 19. bxa5 Qxa5 20. Qb3 $14 {The engine thinks that we still have a +0,30 advantage, but after the exchange of the 'a' and 'b' pawns, Black's drawing chances increase significantly. That's why I would prefer to avoid moves like 15.a4.}) 17. g3 $1 {[%csl Rg6] A typically good move, limiting Black's knight on g6.} Be7 18. h4 h6 19. Kg2 {[%csl Gf3,Gg2,Gh4] White has a very nice setup and can now start some kingside operations.} Rae8 20. Nh2 $1 {[%cal Gd1g4] Very good move: Qg4 is next.} Bd8 21. axb5 {This is a logical move because White opens the 'a' file for the rook.} (21. c4 $1 {Was immediately winning, according to the engine.}) 21... axb5 22. Ra6 Kh7 23. Qh5 Ne7 {White got a fantastic, close-to-winning position. Now, I like the engine's recommendation.} 24. Nf3 $1 {[%cal Gf3g5] Ng5 is a threat.} (24. Rfa1 {Was played by Leko. White is still better, but after a strong defense from Kasimdzhanov, the game ended in a draw.}) 24... Kg8 25. Ng1 $18 {[%csl Gh3][%cal Gg1h3] A fantastic move! Our knight will go to h3, where Ng5 options are always available, it supports eventually f2-f4, but it also defends the f2 pawn. The Nf3-Ng1-Nh3 idea is a very instructive strategic exercise!}) 11. Nxd4 exd4 12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 13. Bxe6 fxe6 14. Qg4 {[%cal Gc7c6,Gc6c5,Gc5c4,Ya8c8,Gh2h4,Gc1g5,Yh4h5,Yh5h6,Yf2f4] White gets a risk-free position, but Black is solid. White's main ideas are f4 or h4, followed by h5-h6 or by Bg5. Black's main plan is to play c5-c4 and generate a counterplay on the 'c' file. Of course, we cannot check all Black's possible moves because every move is possible in these positions, but it's important to understand the ideas.} Qd7 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gc5c4,Ga8c8] This is Black's most common continuation. Black leaves the c8 square for a rook so that he can now execute his main c5-c4-Rc8 plan.} (14... Qc8 {[%cal Ge6e5] Black prepares e5.} 15. f4 $1 e5 16. f5 $14 {[%cal Gf1f3,Gf3h3] White gets an interesting position where he could develop a kingside attack by playing Rf3-Rh3. Let's check a model game:} c5 17. Bg5 Kh8 18. Rf3 c4 {Leko-Caruana, 2013.} 19. Raf1 $1 {This useful move would have been stronger, because in case of} (19. Rh3 {was played by Leko, but Black has the strong} Bxg5 $1 20. Qxg5 Rf6 $13 {And his position is fine. I told you that Rf3-Rh3 is White's plan, but it doesn't mean that you need to go for it immediately.}) 19... Bxg5 20. Qxg5 Rf6 {We can change plan and play} 21. g4 $16 {[%cal Gg5h4,Gg4g5] With Qh4-g5 ideas.}) 15. b3 $1 {A strong move: first of all, we place our queenside pawns in the best possible way:} (15. f4 $6 {Was played in the very important game Karjakin-Carlsen, WC 2016. I don't like f4, because White loses some other plans like h4-Bg5.} c5 16. f5 Rae8 17. Bd2 c4 18. h3 c3 $13 {Black created a good counterplay in Karjakin-Carlsen, WC 2016.}) 15... c5 16. a4 $1 {[%csl Ga4,Gb3,Gc2,Gd3] This is White's ideal structure on the queenside. Only now can we start playing on the kingside.} c4 {This is Black's most natural move. Now, we can use the h4-Bg5 idea, like in the Kramnik-Shirov game, or play another prophylactic move Bd2!?} 17. h4 {[%cal Gc1g5,Gh4h5] White has two ideas: Bg5 or h5.} (17. Bd2 $5 {deserves attention, but maybe Black can play} c3 {and it will be difficult to break-through.}) 17... cxd3 18. cxd3 {This is a standard position that we can get in this line. Black has, of course, a lot of possible continuations.} b4 {Shirov doesn't allow White to open any other line on the queenside.} (18... Rfc8 {It may look like the most natural move, but it's already an inaccuracy.} 19. axb5 $1 axb5 20. Bf4 $14 {[%cal Ya1a8,Yc1c8] Black's problem is that White will get at least one of the 'a' and 'c' files.}) 19. Bd2 {[%csl Gc3,Gd2][%cal Gd2c3] The bishop is well-placed on d2, ad it controls the important c3 square.} a5 20. Rac1 {[%cal Gd2g5,Gf6g5,Gh4g5,Yf2f4,Yf4f5,Rh4h5,Rh5h6]} Rac8 21. Rc4 (21. h5 $5 {Also deserves attention, where probably Black's best is} Rc3 $1 22. Bxc3 dxc3 23. h6 $36 {And we get an interesting position where Black has almost full compensation for the missing exchange, but we are the only one still trying.}) 21... Rxc4 22. dxc4 {An engine will always show you a +0,10 evaluation, but this game clearly shows that it's not easy to play from the Black's side.} Qf7 23. h5 d3 $2 {Already a serious mistake.} (23... d5 $1 {Was probably Black's best continuation, but not an easy one!} 24. exd5 exd5 25. c5 d3 $1 26. h6 Bc3 $1 27. Be3 Qf5 28. Qxf5 Rxf5 29. c6 d4 30. c7 Rc5 31. Bf4 g6 $11 32. Rd1 d2 33. Kf1 Kf7 $11 {And it should be a draw.}) 24. h6 $1 d5 25. hxg7 Bxg7 26. cxd5 exd5 27. e5 $1 Qg6 {Kramnik-Shirov, 2017. Now, White missed the winning idea:} 28. Qxg6 $1 hxg6 29. f4 $18 {[%cal Gf1f3,Gf3d3] Rf3-Rxd3 next, and Black can resign. CONCLUSIONS: 9...Be6 is a very serious option for Black. After we play 10.Nd5, we get interesting positions in case of 10...Bxd5 or 10...Na5. Black's best continuation is 10...Nd4!, where White achieves a slightly better and risk-free position, but Black is very solid. Against an engine, you will never win these positions, but practice has shown that OTB is quite unpleasant to play from the Black's side, and if you get confident with the ideas we have studied in this chapter, you can definitely put pressure on your opponent.} *

