1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. d3 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. a3 O-O 9. Nc3 Na5 {This is Black's second most common move.} 10. Ba2 Be6 {Compared to the previous chapter 9...Be6, White shouldn't now play Nd5 because Nxd5 will be possible.} (10... c5 {Black plays in Chigorin style, but it doesn't work great here:} 11. b4 Nc6 (11... cxb4 12. axb4 Nc6 {is an important variation, because here White has} 13. Nd5 $1 {And the b4 pawn is defended by tactical measures because, after Nxd5-Bxd5, Nxb4 is impossible because of the rook on a8. This is a very important detail and will be why many strong players are starting nowadays with 9...Rb8!?} Nxd5 (13... Be6 14. Bd2 $14 {White gets a typically slightly better position. According to the engine, it's already +0,60, which doesn't happen often in the Classical Spanish!}) 14. Bxd5 Bb7 15. c3 Qd7 16. Bd2 $14 {[%cal Gd1e2,Ga1a3,Gf1a1,Yc3c4] We can continue with Qe2 and then double our rooks on the 'a' file (Ra3-Rfa1) . At some point, c3-c4 might be an idea. White has a pleasant edge.}) 12. Nd5 $1 {Same idea as in the 11...cxb4 12.axb4 Nc6 variation.} Be6 (12... a5 {Was recently tried by Sindarov, but White is better after} 13. c4 $1 Nxd5 14. exd5 Nd4 15. Nxd4 cxd4 (15... exd4 16. bxc5 bxc4 (16... dxc5 $2 17. cxb5 $16) 17. cxd6 Bxd6 18. dxc4 $14) 16. cxb5 a4 {Syleymanli-Sindarov, 2024.} 17. f4 $14 Bd7 18. Bd2 $5 (18. fxe5 $5 {deserves attention.} dxe5 19. d6 Bxd6 20. Qh5 Be6 21. Bxe6 fxe6 22. Bd2 $14 {It's a very unpleasant position for Black.}) 18... Bxb5 19. Qf3 $14 {[%cal Ga1c1] Rac1 next.}) 13. Nxf6+ $5 Bxf6 14. Bxe6 fxe6 15. bxc5 dxc5 16. Be3 Nd4 17. Nd2 $14 {[%cal Gc2c3,Ya3a4] We can continue with a4 or c3, and we have a non-standard where it might be difficult to play from the Black's side.}) 11. Bg5 $5 {This is White's most interesting continuation, in my opinion.} (11. Nd5 $6 Nxd5 $15 {This is a huge difference between the 9...Be6 and the 9...Na5 10.Ba2 Be6 variations.}) (11. d4 {this move is not challenging.} Bxa2 12. Rxa2 Re8 $11 {Black was fine in Karjakin-Carlsen, WC 2016.}) (11. b4 {Before preparing for this course, this move was going to be my main recommendation, but I realized that Black has a new idea:} Bxa2 12. Rxa2 (12. Nxa2 $5 {deserves attention. The idea is that after} Nc6 {White can play} 13. c4 {I don't believe too much in this direction, but it might be that White's position will be slightly preferable after, for example} Nd4 14. Nc3 c6 15. Rb1 $13) 12... Nc6 13. Bg5 {In the past, Black was mainly playing 13...Ng4 or 13...Qd7, and I have interesting ideas there, but Black has found a new way:} h6 $1 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Nd5 Nd4 $1 {Which was played in the recent game Leko-Ragger, 2024 Olympiad. I was not able to find interesting ideas for White in this position. For example:} 16. c4 $5 {Was played by Leko, but Ragger has shown a very clear way for equality:} (16. c3 Nxf3+ 17. Qxf3 Bg5 $11 {[%cal Gc7c6,Ya6a5] is just fine for Black. c6 will be his next move.}) (16. Nxd4 exd4 17. a4 c6 $11 {You can try 18.Nxf6+ or 18.Nf4, but the position is just equal.}) 16... Ne6 $1 17. cxb5 axb5 18. Qc2 Ra6 $1 {[%cal Gc7c6] Black prepares c6.} 19. a4 c6 20. Ne3 Bg5 $11 {Black had zero problems in Leko-Ragger, 2024.}) 11... c5 $1 {This is Black's strongest continuation. Compared to 10...c5, now our plan b4-Nc6-Nd5 is less strong.} (11... h6 {This is not a popular move, but it's definitely a possible one.} 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. Nd5 c6 {This position was reached in Van Foreest-Grigoryan, 2015.} 14. Nxf6+ $14 Qxf6 15. Bxe6 Qxe6 16. Qd2 $1 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gd2a5]} Nb7 {[%csl Rb7,Re6] It seems that White doesn't have much, but our pieces are better placed, and we can continue with} 17. Rae1 $1 {[%csl Gf1][%cal Yf3h4,Gd3d4] We can play for d3-d4 or for Nh4-f4 (that's why we keep a rook on f1) . For example:} c5 {Black stops d4, but we can now play} (17... Rad8 18. d4 $14 {[%cal Gd2c3] Qc3 next, and White's position is definitely more pleasant.}) 18. Nh4 $36 {[%cal Gh4f5,Gf2f4] Nf5 or f4 next, and we have an initiative.}) (11... Bxa2 12. Rxa2 Nc6 {Black decides to retreat his knight to a good square, but after} (12... c5 $6 {This is a strategic mistake because Black weakens the d5 square:} 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. b4 Nc6 15. Nd5 $14 {White has a serious positional plus.}) (12... c6 {Black prevents Nd5, but after} 13. b4 {[%csl Ra5] The knight must retreat to the passive b7 square.} Nb7 14. d4 Nd7 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. Qd3 $14 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gf1a1,Ga3a4] We can continue with Rfa1-a4.}) 13. a4 $1 b4 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Nd5 a5 16. c3 $14 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Rc6d4] Black was not in time to play Nd4, which means that our knight on d5 will stay there for some time.}) 12. Bxf6 {By playing this typical exchange, we get access to the d5 square. The only question will be " Is it enough to get an advantage ?"} (12. b4 Nc6 13. Nd5 Rc8 $13 {Black doesn't have any problem.}) 12... Bxf6 13. Nd5 {Black now has two main plans: g6-Bg7, or Nc6, followed by a5 and some queenside play.} Nc6 (13... g6 {[%cal Gf6g7]} 14. Qd2 Bg7 15. b4 Nc6 16. c3 {We get a balanced and playable position, which should be more interesting to play from the White's side. For example:} Ne7 (16... Rc8 {Adams-Sargysian, 2023.} 17. bxc5 $14 dxc5 18. a4 {Our idea is to create an initiative on the queenside.} Qd6 (18... Ne7 $6 {A very logical move for a human, but an inaccuracy!} 19. Ne3 $1 Bxa2 20. Rxa2 $14 {Unpleasant for Black.}) 19. axb5 axb5 20. Rfb1 Rb8 21. Rb2 $36 {[%cal Ga1b1,Yf3g5] We have some initiative. We can continue with Rab1 and sometimes with Ng5. If Black plays Ne7, we will again play Ne3 (as was shown in the 18...Ne7 note) .}) 17. Ne3 $1 (17. Nxe7+ $6 Qxe7 $11 {After the exchange of the knights Black is absolutely fine, as happened in the game Carlsen-Caruana, 2023.}) 17... Bxa2 $14 {This is Blakc's strongest continuation, according to the engine.} (17... Qd7 {This natural move was played twice in practice, but after} 18. bxc5 $14 dxc5 19. a4 $14 {We get a typical interesting queenside play as was explained in the 16...Rc8 note.}) 18. Qxa2 $5 {We do not allow d5, but Black can now play} (18. Rxa2 {allows} d5 $1 19. bxc5 Rc8 {Which should still be investigated, but the engine is confident that Black equalizes.}) 18... a5 $1 {I don't think that we can fight for a real advantage, but we can for sure get a playable position in different ways. For example:} 19. Rab1 (19. bxc5 dxc5 20. Rfd1 $13) 19... Qd7 $1 20. Rfc1 cxb4 21. cxb4 axb4 22. Rxb4 $13 {I don't think that this is a 100% draw.}) 14. a4 $1 {This is a very important detail: we do not allow Black to place his pawns on b4 and a5, as in the 14.c3 variation.} (14. c3 {is White's most common continuation, but Black can now play} a5 $1 {[%cal Ga5a4] With the idea a4, and if we play} 15. a4 {He is in time to play} b4 $13 {And he gets a good queenside counterplay, and the position is just equal.}) 14... b4 {This is Black's most common continuation, but we can now play} (14... g6 15. c3 {Compared to 14.c3, Black is not in time now to play b4+a5.} Bg7 {[%cal Gc6e7] Black is ready for Ne7.} (15... b4 $6 16. cxb4 cxb4 17. Rc1 Rc8 18. Bc4 $14) 16. Ne3 {We get a playable position, where I don't want to say that we are better, but the game continues, and Black needs to understand how to continue. Let's check some model games.} b4 $1 (16... Bh6 $2 {Was played in Domingues-Sevian, but White got immediately a better position:} 17. Bxe6 fxe6 18. axb5 axb5 19. Rxa8 Qxa8 20. Qb3 $16 {[%csl Rb5,Re6][%cal Gb3e6,Gb3b5]}) (16... Bd7 {Black decides to keep the bishops.} 17. Bd5 Qe7 {Pranav-Tabatabei, 2023.} (17... Qc7 $2 {Jiang-Wongso, 2023.} 18. axb5 $1 axb5 19. Rxa8 Rxa8 20. Ng5 Be8 21. f4 $40 {White has a winning attack.}) 18. h4 $14 {[%cal Gf3g5,Gh4h5] We prepare h5 or Ng5 ideas.}) 17. a5 $5 {An interesting idea played by MVL in 2017.} (17. Bd5 Bxd5 18. Nxd5 Ne7 19. Nxe7+ Qxe7 20. cxb4 cxb4 21. Qb3 a5 22. Rac1 Bh6 $1 23. Rc4 $13 {I would take White, but the position is objectively equal.}) 17... Nxa5 $14 {This is Black's correct reaction, without he inclusion of bxc3-bxc3.} (17... bxc3 $6 {As you can see, even for 2650+ GrandMasters, it's not easy to find the right reaction.} 18. bxc3 Nxa5 19. Bxe6 fxe6 20. Qa4 Nb7 21. Rfb1 {White misses a pawn, but he has a serious initiative on the queenside.} Qc7 22. Qc4 (22. Nc4 $14 {[%cal Gb1b6] Deserves attention, with the idea Rb6.}) 22... Qd7 23. Ng5 Nd8 24. Rxa6 Rxa6 25. Qxa6 {Black's position has objectively improved, but it's still not easy to play from the practical point of view, as was shown in this game:} Bh6 $1 26. Nf3 Bxe3 27. fxe3 Nf7 28. Rb7 Qd8 29. Qa7 {According to the engine, White has only a minimal advantage (+0,05) , but I am sure that all the players in the world would take White!} Qf6 30. h3 g5 31. Re7 {Engine shows only +0,05, but you can see how easy it is to lose from the Black's side in just a few moves:} Qh6 $6 (31... g4 $1 {Was Black's right reaction, and only after} 32. hxg4 Qh6 $11 {is strong.}) 32. Nh2 $1 c4 $2 {Second mistake, now 13.d4 would have given White a serious advantage.} 33. Ng4 $6 {White spoils the advantage.} (33. d4 $16) 33... Qg6 34. Qd7 Rd8 35. Qc7 Rf8 36. Qxc4 Nd8 {Even this is equal, according to the engine! But who would like to play from the Black's side? After many other moves, White finally won the game in MVL-Piorun, 2017.}) 18. Bxe6 (18. Bd5 $5 {deserves attention.} Bxd5 19. Nxd5 Nc6 20. Nd2 $44 {For sure, White has enough compensation, and I am not sure if from the practical point of view we also have the initiative.}) 18... fxe6 19. Ng5 $5 {This is my recommendation.} (19. Qa4 Nb7 $11 {According to the engine, this position is improved for Black compared to the same one with bxc3-bxc3 included, but who will understand it?}) 19... Qxg5 (19... Re8 20. Qf3 $13 {Leads to an unclear, interesting position.}) 20. Rxa5 $36 {We have a very easy play and a little more than enough compensation for the pawn.}) 15. a5 $1 g6 $1 {Black's most logical continuation, with the idea to improve the bishop on g7.} (15... Nxa5 $2 {Would be a serious mistake because of} 16. Nxf6+ gxf6 17. Bd5 Bxd5 18. exd5 $16 {[%cal Gf3h4,Gh4f5] Nh4-Nf5 next, and White has a good advantage.}) (15... Na7 $6 {Was played in the game Saric-Wojtaszek, 2021.} 16. c3 bxc3 17. bxc3 Nb5 18. Qc2 Rb8 19. h3 Nc7 {Saric-Wojtaszek, 2021.} 20. Nb6 $14 {White has serious pressure. For example:} Na8 21. Nxa8 Rxa8 22. Nd2 $16 {[%cal Gd2c4,Ya2e6,Yf7e6] We can continue with Nc4 or Bxe6-fxe6-Nc4.}) 16. c3 Rb8 $14 {Black's only move to stay in the game.} ({The natural} 16... Bg7 $6 {is a mistake for tactical reasons:} 17. cxb4 cxb4 18. Nb6 $1 Rb8 19. Bxe6 fxe6 20. Qa4 $16) (16... bxc3 $6 {This is a positional mistake.} 17. bxc3 Bg7 {Vokhidov-Kobo, 2022.} 18. Nb6 $1 Rb8 19. Qa4 Qc7 20. Rfb1 $18 {White dominates the queenside and, according to the engine, our position is already winning.}) 17. Bc4 {[%csl Ra6] Black has to think about the a6 pawn.} (17. Qa4 Bd7 $13 {is Black's idea.}) 17... Bxd5 $1 18. Bxd5 Ne7 19. Ba2 $14 {We get an opposite-color-bishop middlegame, where our bishop is superior. For sure, Black's position is very solid, but we are still the ones trying, and the game continues. CONCLUSIONS: 9...Na5 is one of Black's strongest and most concrete continuations. Although it is not always possible to have an objective advantage if our opponent is extremely well-prepared, our positions are always playable and more pleasant to play for us than for our opponent. But, in most of the games, our opponent is not prepared like a 2700+ GrandMaster. In this case, we will definitely be able to pose serious practical problems.} *

