1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. d3 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. a3 O-O 9. Nc3 {In the previous chapters, we have analyzed Black's most common options. But the position is very flexible, and also other less-standard moves are possible.} h6 {Of course, this useful move is also possible.} (9... Nd4 {Of course, this move has to be mentioned because we always need to be ready against Black's options that force a structural change.} 10. Nxd4 exd4 11. Ne2 c5 12. Bg5 {We have a long-term plus thanks to the better structure, for example:} Be6 {Black's most common continuation.} (12... Nd7 13. Bd2 (13. Bxe7 Qxe7 $13 {The exchange of the bishops makes Black's life easier.}) 13... Nf6 {[%csl Gd2][%cal Gc1d2] Was played in the game Alekseev-Sjugirov, 2016. It's true that White needs to find a plan if he doesn't want to repeat moves, but we got for free the Bd2 useful move.} 14. Ng3 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gd1f3] Our idea is f4-Qf3 (eventually h3 first) , and we have a very pleasant game.} Be6 15. Ba2 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gd1f3] A cute move: we want to exchange the bishops on our terms.}) 13. Bxf6 $1 {[%csl Gd5] We are playing for the d5 square.} Bxf6 14. Nf4 Qe7 (14... Bxb3 $2 15. cxb3 $16 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gf4d5] Our knight will have the strong outpost on d5.}) 15. Nd5 $1 Qd8 (15... Bxd5 $2 16. Bxd5 $18 {[%csl Gd5,Rf6] This is a very instructive position: Our bishop is so much stronger than Black's one that, according to the engine, White already has a winning advantage.}) 16. a4 $14 {Very unpleasant position for Black. We can conclude by saying that 9...Nd4 forces a structural change that favors White.}) (9... Rb8 {This mysterious move has been played by many strong GrandMasters.} 10. Be3 {It's difficult to say which move is White's best, if h3, Be3, or some other move. Nobody can answer these questions. I will suggest Be3, but that doesn't mean that you cannot play another move.} (10. Z0 {We can see Black's idea if we give him the move:} Na5 11. Ba2 c5 12. b4 cxb4 13. axb4 Nc6 $2 {If Black's rook were on a8, White's strongest continuation would have been Nd5! Nfxd5 Is not possible now because after} 14. Nd5 {Bxd5} Nxb4 $18 {[%csl Ra8,Gb8][%cal Rd5a8] Black's rook is on b8, and not on a8!}) (10. Ba2 $5 {Was tried by Cheparinov, but I am afraid that after} a5 $13 {Black gets a good counterplay.}) 10... Na5 {Black continues with his standard plan.} 11. Ba2 c5 12. Nd5 {[%cal Gb2b4] With our knight on d5, we are ready to play b4.} Nxd5 (12... c4 13. Nxe7+ Qxe7 14. h3 $14 {[%cal Yd1e1,Yb2b3] White is slightly better, thanks to the pair of bishops. A good plan could be Qe1, followed by b3.}) 13. Bxd5 Bb7 14. b4 {White's most concrete continuation.} (14. Ba2 $5 {Is my main recommendation.} Nc6 15. c3 {[%cal Gb2b4] our idea is to play b4, while after} a5 16. Qe2 $14 {[%cal Gd3d4,Yf1b1,Yb2b4] We can slowly prepare d4 or b4 (for example, after preparing it with Rfb1) .} a4 {Is a logical move for Black, fixing the queenside.} 17. d4 cxd4 18. cxd4 exd4 19. Nxd4 $14 {Black still needs to work to prove equality.}) 14... Bxd5 15. exd5 Nb7 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gf7f5] Black's knight on b7 is passive, but Black hopes to generate a counterplay by playing f5.} 16. Re1 {was played by Anand in a magistral game.} (16. Rc1 $5 {Deserves attention. For example:} f5 17. c4 {Black still needs to understand how to continue.}) 16... f5 17. bxc5 dxc5 18. Nxe5 Qxd5 19. Bf4 (19. f4 {[%cal Gc2c4] Was probably stronger, always with the idea c2-c4.}) 19... Rbe8 $6 {Wojtaszek made just one small mistake, and Anand overtook the initiative like a real tiger!} (19... Bf6 $1 20. c4 Qd4 $13 {Was Black's best continuation.}) 20. c4 $1 Qd4 21. Nc6 Qxf4 22. Nxe7+ Kh8 23. Ra2 {[%cal Ga2e2] White wants to double the rooks on the 'e' file.} Nd6 24. Rae2 Qg5 25. Re6 bxc4 26. g3 cxd3 27. f4 Qg4 28. Qxg4 fxg4 29. Rxd6 c4 30. Rd4 $18 {Anand-Wojtaszek, 2022. What a game!}) 10. h3 Rb8 {This is very similar to 9...Rb8, only that now the moves h3-h6 have been included.} (10... Re8 {This is a standard continuation.} 11. Nd5 Bf8 $6 {was played in the game Anand-Caruana, 2018.} (11... Be6 12. Be3 Bf8 13. Rc1 $36 {[%cal Gc2c4] We can consider c4 ideas.}) 12. Nxf6+ $14 {Was White's strongest continuation.} Qxf6 13. Bd5 $1 {By playing this move, we fix Black's knight on c6 and Black's bishop, who will need to defend the knight.} Bd7 14. Nh2 $16 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gd1h5,Gh2g4] White has a serious advantage because we are ready for direct ideas like Qh5-Ng4 or f4.}) 11. Be3 {We can still go for our main idea, and we can now check what happens if Black plays a standard move like} Re8 {Which was tried by many strong players, including Gukesh, Esipenko, Deac, Dubov, Artemiev, Matlakov...} 12. Nd5 Bf8 13. c4 $5 {I like this move, which was tried in the recent high-level game Giri-Gukesh, Sinquifield Cup 2024.} ({Compared to 10..:Re8, now the moves Be3-Rb8 have been included, which means that after} 13. Nxf6+ Qxf6 14. Bd5 {Black's rook is not on a8, and Black can just play} (14. Nh2 {Is not so interesting now, because Black can play} Be6 $11 {With a solid position.}) 14... Ne7 $13) 13... Bd7 $1 {As we will see, Gukesh was really well prepared and played all the best moves!} (13... Na5 14. Ba2 bxc4 {Seems great for Black, but it doesn't work for tactical reasons:} 15. Nxf6+ $1 Qxf6 $4 (15... gxf6 {doesn't lose material, but is of course very dangerous:} 16. Nh4 $1 Rxb2 17. dxc4 $16 {[%cal Gd1h5,Gc4c5] Qh5 or c5 next, and White has a serious advantage.}) 16. Qa4 $18 {[%csl Ra5,Re8][%cal Ga4a5,Ga4e8] And Black loses material.}) 14. Qd2 $1 {[%csl Ya5][%cal Gd2a5,Rc6a5,Gf1c1] A strong prophylactic move against Na5. Our idea is to play on the 'c' file with, for example, Rfc1.} bxc4 $1 15. Bxc4 Nxd5 16. Bxd5 Ne7 (16... Qf6 $5 {Was another computer-style possibility.} 17. Rfc1 Ne7 18. Rxc7 Nxd5 19. Rxd7 {Every human would think that White has a big advantage, but the engine finds:} Qe6 $1 (19... Nxe3 $6 {is a bad move order, because after} 20. fxe3 Qe6 {White can play} 21. Rc7 $1 Qb3 22. Rc2 $14) 20. Ra7 Nxe3 21. fxe3 d5 $1 {And, somehow, the engine holds:} (21... Qb3 22. Rc1 Qxb2 23. Rxa6 $14 {This is, of course, not a 100% draw.}) 22. exd5 (22. Rc1 Qb6 23. Rcc7 dxe4 24. dxe4 Bc5 $1 25. Qd5 Bxe3+ 26. Kf1 Qb5+ $11) 22... Qb6 $1 {Black wants to take on d5, but first, he forces our rook to stay on c7.} 23. Rd7 Qb5 24. Rc7 Qxd5 25. b4 {It's not White's only move, but I want to show you the engine's idea.} e4 26. dxe4 Qxe4 27. Re1 Rbc8 $44 {Black has enough compensation for the pawn. 16...Qf6 might be good for computer games, but for a human is very difficult to sacrifice a pawn like this, where White has a lot of options, and Black always needs to find the best move to maintain the compensation. If it was easy, Gukesh would have played it!}) 17. Bc4 $1 {[%csl Ra6] We attack the a6 pawn and don't allow Black to play c5 in time.} (17. Ba2 {allows} c5 $11 {[%cal Rb2b4,Rd3d4] And White can no longer play for b4 or d4.}) 17... c6 $3 {This was Gukesh's preparation!} (17... Qc8 {Would be a very natural move for a human, but after} 18. b4 $14 {[%cal Gf1c1] Rfc1 next, and White has the advantage.}) 18. b4 $14 {This is my recommendation to improve the Giri-Gukesh game.} (18. Bxa6 {was played by Giri, but after} d5 $1 {[%csl Ra6] The bishop doesn't have too many squares.} 19. Nxe5 {and the game ended in a draw by repetition:} Ra8 20. Bb7 Rb8 $11 {Giri-Gukesh, Sinquifield Cup 2024.}) 18... d5 19. Ba2 Ng6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gg6e5] Black has to defend the e5 pawn.} ({An important detail is that} 19... d4 $2 {is not possible because of} 20. Nxe5 $18) 20. exd5 cxd5 21. Bxd5 Bxh3 $1 22. Be4 (22. Bxf7+ Kxf7 23. gxh3 Kg8 $44 {[%csl Rf2,Rh3] We keep an extra pawn, but Black has good compensation because of our weak kingside structure.}) 22... Bg4 23. Rac1 $14 {The game still goes on, and White's position seems easier to play. Of course, if you play against Gukesh and he knows another ten best engine's moves, you will never win, but against a normal player not competing in the World Championship match, this still seems very playable. CONCLUSIONS: Black can play 9...h6, or 9...Rb8 because they are both solid moves that improve the position. But White has a lot of options, and the game is still alive everywhere, even in the Giri-Gukesh game!} *

