1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. d3 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. a3 O-O 9. Nc3 Bg4 {[%cal Gg4f3,Gc6d4] This is Back's most common and most concrete continuation. By immediately pinning the knight, he aims for a quick Nd4 idea.} 10. Be3 {[%cal Ge3d4] We have to play this move to take control of the important d4 square.} (10. h3 $6 {Is not a good option, because after} Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Nd4 12. Qd1 Nxb3 13. cxb3 d5 $36 {Black immediately has the more comfortable game.}) 10... Nd4 {This is Black's critical and most principled continuation. It has been played in more than 600 games.} (10... Qd7 11. h3 Be6 $1 {This is Black's best continuation, but it's not in the spirit of 9...Bg4.} (11... Bh5 $6 {Is Black's most popular continuation, but the bishop is misplaced on h5, and after} 12. Nd5 $1 {White has a serious advantage. For example:} Nxd5 13. Bxd5 Bg6 {Was played in the game Heberla-Socko, 2022.} 14. c4 $16 {[%cal Ga1c1] I like this idea. We will continue with Rc1 and put pressure on the 'c' file.}) 12. Nd5 Bd8 13. Rc1 $14 {[%cal Gc2c4] We prepare c4 ideas.} h6 {Black makes useful moves, and we can do the same.} (13... Bxd5 14. exd5 Ne7 15. c4 $14) 14. Re1 Rb8 {Sooner or later we might go for} 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. Bxe6 Qxe6 17. b4 $14 {[%cal Gc2c4] c4 next, and we have the better game.}) 11. Bxd4 exd4 12. Nd5 {After White plays h3, Black will be compelled to capture on f3; retreating the bishop would leave the d4 pawn undefended. Once Black exchanges his bishop for our knight on f3, we can proceed by trading the remaining pair of knights, achieving an optimal setup: a position with opposite-colored bishops, where our bishop stands significantly stronger.} c6 {This is a tricky move, and it's extremely important for White to know the right reaction.} (12... h6 {Let's better illustrate the concept by seeing what happens if Black plays a waiting move.} 13. h3 {we continue with our planned move. Black's bishop cannot retreat on d7 because the d4 pawn would be hanging, and it cannot go to h5 because of g4, so} Bxf3 {is forced. We can now exchange the knights with check} 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. Qxf3 {And we have our ideal set-up: an opposite-color bishop position. It is evident that our bishop is much more active than Black's one. Our idea is to play a4, and eventually, we can even fight for the 'a' line if our opponent allows us to play Bd5.} c6 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Gc6d5,Yb3d5] This is a logical move for Black, because it prevents Bd5.} 16. a4 Qd7 {Black's position may seem solid and difficult to break, but White has different good plans, for example:} 17. Qh5 {[%cal Gf2f4] We are preparing f4.} Ra7 {[%cal Gg8h7,Gg7g6] Black plays a prophylactic move with the idea of continuing with Kh7-g6.} (17... Kh7 $2 {This move is not good because White can play} 18. axb5 $1 {And Black cannot recapture with the 'a' pawn because after Rxa8-Rxa8, the f7 pawn will be hanging. On the other hand, cxb6 would be a big positional concession: after Bd5, White is much better.}) 18. h4 $5 {We improve our kingside.} Kh7 19. g3 g6 20. Qf3 (20. Qe2 {is not so precise because of} Qh3 $13 {And Black has some counterplay. We do not need to rush; it is better to play slow moves without allowing Black any counterplay.}) 20... Kg7 21. Kh2 {[%csl Rh3][%cal Gh2h3,Yf3g2,Yf3e2,Rd7h3] We prevents Qh3 ideas, and we are ready for Qg2 (or Qe2) and f4.} h5 22. Qg2 Raa8 {It's difficult to suggest a good plan for Black; probably his best strategy is to wait.} 23. f4 Ra7 24. Rf2 {[%cal Ga1f1] We double our rooks on the 'f' file.} Qd8 (24... Raa8 {Black should already be careful, because if he continues to play the same moves, then after} 25. Raf1 Ra7 {White has the decisive} 26. e5 $1 {[%csl Rf7] Where Black cannot take because of concrete problems against the pawn on f7.} Bd8 27. f5 dxe5 28. fxg6 f5 29. Bf7 $16) 25. Raf1 Qe8 {Black waits in this way so that the f7 pawn is well protected. Now, we can continue improving our position (for example Rf1-Qd2-Kf2) , or go for the immediate} 26. f5 $16 {[%cal Yh2h1,Gg3g4] Where it's difficult for Black to move, we can continue with a prophylactic move like Kh1 and then g4.}) (12... c5 {Is Ding's favorite move, and we will analyze it in Chapter 8.}) (12... Nxd5 {Is Aronian's favorite move, and we will analyze it in Chapter 9.}) (12... Nd7 $5 {[%csl Gb3,Gd7] By playing this move, Black's idea is to achieve a position with a knight on d7 against our bishop on b3.} 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 c6 15. Nxe7+ Qxe7 {Our bishop on b3 is very strong, but Black hopes to deal with his activity, and one day, his knight might not be worse than our bishop.} 16. Qg3 {[%cal Gf2f4] Our idea is f4.} Nc5 (16... Rab8 {[%cal Gb5b4] Black plays for a quick b5-b4.} 17. f4 Nc5 18. Ba2 b4 {Has been played in the game Onischuk-Dubov, 2015.} 19. Qf2 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gf2d4] White attacks Black's pawn on d4.} bxa3 20. bxa3 Rb2 21. Bc4 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gf2d4] Black's rook is active, but the d4 pawn is weak, and we plan Rac1-Qxd4.} Rfb8 $14 {This is Black's strongest continuation, and it has a venomous trick.} (21... Qf6 $2 {Logical move played by Dubov, but White is much better after} 22. e5 $1 dxe5 23. fxe5 Qxf2+ 24. Rxf2 $16 {[%csl Rd4,Rf7][%cal Ga1f1,Gf2f4] Black has problems with the f7 pawn but also with the d4 pawn. For example:} Rb7 25. Rf4 Rd7 26. Raf1 $18 {[%cal Ge5e6] e6 next, and Black's position is collapsing.}) 22. Rfe1 $14 {[%cal Ga1c1,Ye4e5] We play a prophylactic move against d5. Our idea is now to play Rac1, and sometimes we might have e5 ideas.} (22. Rac1 $4 d5 $1 23. exd5 cxd5 24. Bxd5 Nxd3 $19)) (16... Rac8 {[%cal Gc6c5,Gc5c4] Black plays for c5-c4.} 17. f4 c5 18. Rae1 {[%cal Ge4e5] Sooner or later we may consider e5.} c4 $6 19. Ba2 $16 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Gg3f2,Gf2d4] We can continue with Qf2, and Black's pawn on d4 is weak. This is the main problem of the c5-c4 plan.}) (16... a5 {[%cal Ga5a4] Black plans to take space on the queenside by playing a5-a4.} 17. f4 (17. a4 $6 Nc5 $11 {Black is immediately fine.}) 17... a4 18. Ba2 Rab8 {[%cal Gb5b4] Black plans b4.} 19. Qf2 $1 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Yf2d4]} c5 20. Rae1 {[%cal Ge1e2,Gf1e1,Ge4e5] White plans to double the rooks on the 'e' file, and then push e5.} Kh8 {In the game Naiditsch-Postny, White played c3, which is possible but not necessary. I suggest continuing with our main idea:} 21. Re2 {[%cal Gf1e1,Ge4e5]} b4 {looks critical.} 22. axb4 Rxb4 {and only now we can play} 23. c3 dxc3 24. bxc3 Rb6 25. e5 $14 {[%cal Gf1e1] Rfe1 next, and Black's position is very risky.}) 17. Ba2 Na4 {By playing this maneuver, Black's idea is to force our rook to stay on b1.} 18. Rab1 c5 19. f4 {[%cal Ge4e5] Sooner or later, our plan will be e5, while it's not easy to find a good counterplay for Black.} Rac8 {This is Black's most common continuation.} 20. Qf2 $14 {[%csl Ya5][%cal Gf2d2,Yd2a5] We want to reposition our queen on d2 because sometimes it may have Qa5 ideas. According to the engine, the evaluation is +0,40, but in a practical game, it could be higher because Black is very passive and without any plan.}) 13. h3 $1 {This is an extremely important move order.} (13. Nxf6+ $6 {Would be a mistake, because after} Bxf6 14. h3 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gf6d4] Black's bishop can now retreat, as the d4 pawn is not hanging.} Bd7 $13 {Black is immediately fine.}) (13. Nxe7+ $6 Qxe7 14. h3 Bh5 $13 {And we don't have g2-g4, because of Nxg4!}) 13... Bxf3 (13... Bh5 $6 14. Nxf6+ $1 Bxf6 15. g4 {Black no longer can sacrifice on g4, and after} Bg6 {[%csl Rg6] His bishop on g6 is very bad, and we can continue with} 16. Nd2 $16 {[%cal Gf2f4] Followed by f4.}) (13... cxd5 $2 {is bad, because after} 14. hxg4 dxe4 15. Nxd4 $1 exd3 16. Qxd3 $14 (16. Re1 $36 {Is another possible direction.}) 16... Nxg4 {White has the very strong continuation} 17. Ne6 $1 fxe6 18. Bxe6+ Kh8 19. Bxg4 $14 {[%csl Gd5,Rf6][%cal Gg4f3,Gf3d5,Re7f6,Yc2c3,Rf6c3] Our bishop is stronger because we can place it on the ideal d5 square, while Black's bishop will not be so strong on f6 because we will limit it by playing c3.}) 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. Qxf3 $14 {[%cal Ga3a4] We achieve our ideal opposite-color bishops' position, which we have already discussed in the 12...h6 variation.} *

