1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. d3 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. a3 O-O 9. Nc3 Bg4 {[%cal Gg4f3,Gc6d4]} 10. Be3 {[%cal Ge3d4]} Nd4 11. Bxd4 exd4 12. Nd5 c5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gb3d5,Yc5d4,Yg4d7] By playing c5, Black defends the d4 pawn and ensures that in the case of h3, his bishop on g4 can retreat because the d4 pawn is no longer hanging. The obvious drawback of this move is that the d5 square is now very weak.} 13. a4 {[%csl Re7][%cal Ga4b5,Ga6b5,Ya1a8,Yd8a8,Rd5e7] We have a huge threat: axb5-axb5-Rxa8-Qxa8-Nxe7+.} (13. h3 {I don't see any need to play this move now because after 12...c5, the bishop on g4 is allowed to retreat, and h3 could just be a waste of time.}) 13... Be6 $1 {Black's only move.} (13... Rc8 $2 {Fights against the threat, but gives up the important 'a' file.} 14. axb5 axb5 15. Ra7 $16 {[%csl Ga7] This is obviously much better for White because we not only have the 'a' file, but we also create problems on the 7th rank.}) 14. Nxf6+ (14. axb5 {Is not good now, because Black can play the intermediate} Bxd5 $11 {which immediately solves all the problems.}) 14... Bxf6 15. Bxe6 fxe6 {This position has been played a lot of times by Ding Liren.} 16. Qe2 {[%cal Ge4e5] This is a useful move. For example, sometimes we might think about e4-e5.} Qd7 {This is Black's most natural move and it was played by Ding and Eljanov. We will now check their games to understand a lot of useful ideas about this structure.} (16... e5 {As a rule, whenever Black plays e6-e5, we should take on b5, but we will discuss this strategic principle later.} 17. axb5 axb5 18. g3 {[%cal Gg1g2] We improve our position.} Qd7 19. Kg2 Qc6 {[%cal Gc5c4] Black's main counterplay is connected with c5-c4.} 20. h4 c4 ({A very interesting aspect is that if Black exchanges all the rooks} 20... Rxa1 21. Rxa1 Ra8 22. Rxa8+ Qxa8 23. Nh2 $16 {Despite the little amount of material left, Black's position is strategically dangerous. We will see a good example of it in the model game Motylev-Eljanov.}) 21. b3 $1 {The next variations allows us to understand some interesting strategic ideas.} cxb3 {This move looks very logical.} (21... c3 {This is Black's best continuation, but after} 22. Nh2 $14 {[%cal Ge2g4,Gh2g4] White has a two-results game.}) 22. cxb3 Rxa1 (22... Qc3 23. Rab1 Rfc8 {Black takes full control of the 'c' file, but after} 24. Rfc1 $1 Qxc1 25. Rxc1 Rxc1 26. Nh2 $16 {[%csl Ge2,Gh2][%cal Ge2g4,Gg4e6,Yh2g4] White has a serious advantage because the queen + the knight can create a lot of threats.}) 23. Rxa1 Qc3 24. Ra6 Qxb3 25. Rxd6 {For a human, this may look unclear, but in these positions, White's attacking chances are real.} Rb8 {This move prevents Rb6, but after} (25... b4 26. Rb6 $16 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gb6b4] We comfortably control the 'b' pawn.}) 26. Nh2 $18 {White prepares a very strong attack, and our position is already winning, according to the engine.}) 17. axb5 $14 {This is my recommendation, but before checking it, we have to analyze 17.b3.} (17. e5 $5 {This is a possibility.} Bxe5 $1 {This is a more accurate recapture.} (17... dxe5 $2 {Would be a mistake, because after} 18. axb5 axb5 19. b3 Qd5 20. Nd2 $16 {[%csl Gd2,Rf6] White is not forced to retake on e5, and we can play a position with a very good knight against a very bad bishop on f6.}) 18. axb5 axb5 19. Nxe5 dxe5 20. Qxe5 Qd5 $14 {/= White has a nominal edge, but Black's position is easier to play than it was before. In my opinion, we should play e4-e5 only when the situation is optimal.}) (17. b3 e5 {This was Ding Liren's choice in the very important last round of Candidates 2018.} (17... Qc7 {[%cal Gg2g3,Gg1g2] Was chosen by Eljanov.} 18. Rfe1 {[%cal Ge4e5] White prepares e5. Rfe1 was not White's only move, and the classical g3-Kg2 plan would have been good as well.} Be5 $6 {This is a bad way to stop the e4-e5 idea.} (18... e5 $1 {This was Black's best continuation, and after} 19. axb5 axb5 20. g3 $14 {[%cal Gg1g2] We have a typical slightly better position which we will discuss later.}) 19. g3 h6 20. Nh4 {The maneuver Nh4-Ng2 was not necessary, but it's not so important to stop on it.} (20. Kg2 {Would have been my choice. For example:} Qf7 21. h4 Qg6 22. axb5 axb5 23. Nd2 $16 {[%cal Gh4h5,Ge2g4] We can continue with h5, and eventually Qg4.}) 20... Qf7 21. Ng2 Bf6 22. Ra2 e5 {Black finally plays e5. (It was better for him to do it at move 18) .} 23. Rea1 $6 {This natural move allowed Black to block all the position.} (23. axb5 $1 {Was White's correct continuation. As a rule, whenever Black plays e5, we should react with axb5.} axb5 24. Rea1 $14 {White has a pleasant initiative.}) 23... Rac8 $2 (23... b4 $1 {This is why axb5-axb5 was a very important exchange. Now, it's difficult for White to create ideas without the possibility of doing something on the queenside.}) 24. axb5 axb5 25. Ra7 {White's position is better.} Rc7 26. Rxc7 Qxc7 27. Ne1 Qc6 28. Qg4 d5 $2 {This was a decisive mistake, and it came because Eljanov underestimated the endgame with queen and knight vs queen and bishop.} (28... Qc8 $14 {Was Black's best defense, but the position remains unpleasant.}) 29. exd5 Qxd5 30. Nf3 c4 31. bxc4 bxc4 32. Nd2 $1 c3 33. Ne4 Qb7 34. Kg2 Kh8 35. h4 Ra8 36. Rxa8+ Qxa8 {Although not too much material is left, Black loses this endgame, which is a very instructive example of pieces' domination.} 37. Qf5 Qd5 38. Qg6 Bd8 39. Qe8+ Kh7 40. h5 Bg5 41. Kh3 Qa2 42. Nd6 {Black resigned in Motylev-Eljanov, 2014.}) 18. axb5 $1 {Was White's right move.} (18. Ra2 $4 {Do you remember the Motylev-Eljanov game? Karjaking did the same mistake, but this time Black answered in the right way.} b4 $1 19. Nd2 Rae8 20. Raa1 Bd8 {It's extremely difficult for White to create ideas now that the queenside is closed.} 21. g3 g5 22. Nc4 Re6 23. a5 Ref6 $13 {Black was absolutely fine in Karjakin-Ding, 2018 Candidates.}) 18... axb5 19. Rfb1 $14 {White is preferable and can press in a likely long game.} ({I really like the g3-Kg2 idea, but here it's not so strong because Black can play} 19. g3 Qh3 $1)) 17... axb5 18. g3 $1 {[%cal Ge4e5] In the last note of the game Karjakin-Ding I have explained you that White's g3-Kg2 plan was not so strong because Black had Qh3! For this reason, we should play g3-Kg2 right now, in my opinion.} e5 {Sooner or later, Black will need to play this move. Otherwise, our e4-e5 idea could be strong one day.} 19. Kg2 Qc6 {[%cal Gc5c4] Black plays for c4.} 20. b3 c4 (20... Rxa1 {you already know that exchanging all rooks is not a good idea for Black.} 21. Rxa1 Ra8 22. Qd1 {We are not against the exchange of the rooks, but let's make Black work to achieve it!} (22. Rxa8+ {The immediate recapture was also possible, but I want to make everything in a more precise way.}) 22... Ra6 23. h4 h6 24. Nh2 Qa8 25. Rxa6 Qxa6 26. Qg4 $16 {We can benefit from the Motylev-Eljanov game to understand that these endgames are really hard for Black.}) 21. bxc4 bxc4 22. Nd2 c3 23. Nc4 $14 {We can play a long game where Black's defensive task is unpleasant. CONCLUSIONS: In the 12...c5 Ding's Defense, it is less crucial to memorize specific moves and far more important to grasp the underlying ideas. If you fully understand the explanations provided in this chapter (and I highly recommend watching the video lesson as well) , you will certainly be able to put significant pressure on your opponent.} *

