1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. d3 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. a3 O-O 9. Nc3 Bg4 {[%cal Gg4f3,Gc6d4]} 10. Be3 Nd4 11. Bxd4 exd4 12. Nd5 Nxd5 {Levon Aronian used this move in many important games. I decided to analyze it separately because it's very important to understand the "mechanism" of the position.} 13. Bxd5 {Black now tries Rb8 or Rc8.} Rc8 {[%cal Gc7c6] Black immediately prepares c6.} (13... Rb8 {[%cal Gg4d7,Gc7c6,Yd5c6,Yb8b6] GM Kravtsiv often employed this move. Black's main idea is Bd7-c6, and in case of Bc6 (which is our move after 13...Rc8) , Black has Rb6.} 14. a4 $1 {Rb8 has a drawback: Black doesn't immediately threat c7-c6, and we can use this time to open the 'a' file for our rook.} (14. h3 {Is very tempting, but Black can play} Bd7 $1 {[%cal Gc7c6] because after} 15. Nxd4 Bf6 16. c3 Bxd4 17. cxd4 c6 18. Bb3 Qf6 $11 {Black regains the pawn and has a good position.}) (14. Bc6 $6 {Doesn't make sense now at least because of} Rb6 $11) 14... Bf6 $14 {This is Black's best and most logical continuation, but it has never been played.} (14... c5 $2 {Is a mistake, because after} 15. axb5 axb5 16. Ra7 $16 {[%csl Ga7][%cal Ga7h7] Our rook is very strong on a7. That's why Black shouldn't move the 'c' pawn.}) (14... b4 $6 {The inclusion of a4-b4 changes everything, and after} 15. h3 Bd7 16. Nxd4 Bf6 17. c3 Bxd4 18. cxd4 c6 {The difference with the same position without a4-b4 included is that White can now play} 19. Bc4 $1 {[%csl Ra6] And Black has problems with the a6 pawn. For example:} Qf6 20. e5 dxe5 21. dxe5 Qxe5 22. d4 {[%cal Gc4a6] We are ready to take on a6.} Qa5 23. Qb3 $16 {[%cal Gf1e1] Rfe1 next, and we have a very serious advantage because our pieces are much more active. The engine already shows +1,30.}) 15. axb5 axb5 16. Qe2 {[%cal Ga1a7,Gf1a1] This is a useful move, because we prepare Ra7-Rfa1. Black's position is not losing objectively, but it's very hard to play. For example:} g6 {Maybe Black's best strategy is to improve the position.} (16... Qd7 {[%cal Gc7c6] Looks logical, because Black prepares c6, but after} 17. h3 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Rg4d7] Black can no longer play Bd7, while after} Be6 18. Bxe6 Qxe6 (18... fxe6 19. e5 $14) 19. Ra7 $14 {We have a very pleasant edge.}) (16... Bd7 {Black prepares c6, but we can use this time to double our rooks on the 'a' file.} 17. Ra7 c6 18. Bb3 Ra8 19. Rfa1 Rxa7 20. Rxa7 $14 {[%csl Ga7] We have a strong rook on a7, and it's unpleasant to play from the Black's side.}) 17. h3 Bd7 18. Ra7 Kg7 {Black waits and slowly improves his position.} (18... c6 {Once again, after Black moves his c7 pawn, our rook on a7 becomes stronger:} 19. Bb3 Ra8 20. Rfa1 Rxa7 21. Rxa7 $14 {[%csl Ga7][%cal Ga7h7]}) 19. Rfa1 $14 (19. Bb7 $5 {Is an interesting move shown by the engine, but it looks too deep.})) 14. Bc6 $5 {This is, in my opinion, White's most promising continuation. It looks artificial, but it's very important for us to stop c7-c6.} (14. Bb7 {is not winning a pawn because after} Rb8 15. Bxa6 $4 {Black can simply play} Rb6 $19 {Winning our bishop.}) (14. a4 {This was White's best after 13..Rb8, but here Black is in time to concretely equalize:} c6 15. Bb3 d5 $1 16. exd5 c5 $11 {[%cal Gc5c4] c4 next, and Black is fine.}) (14. h3 Bd7 $1 15. Nxd4 Bf6 {We have already seen this idea in the 13..:Rb8 variation.} 16. c3 Bxd4 17. cxd4 c6 18. Bb3 Qf6 $11) 14... Bf6 {[%csl Gd4,Yg4][%cal Gf6d4,Yg4e6,Yg4d7] This is Black's most common and logical move because he defends the d4 pawn, and the bishop on g4 is flexible now.} (14... Bd7 $2 {Would be a serious mistake, because after} 15. Bxd7 Qxd7 16. Nxd4 Bf6 17. c3 Bxd4 18. cxd4 $16 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Rd8f6] Black doesn't have Qf6 ideas, and White is just a pawn up.}) (14... Rb8 {[%cal Gb8b6,Yc6d5,Yc7c6] Black prepares Rb6-Bd6-c5.} 15. h3 $1 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 Rb6 17. Bd5 c6 18. Bb3 $14 {[%csl Gb3,Re7] We have a typical opposite-color bishops middlegame, where our bishop is stronger.}) 15. a4 $1 {We use this time to open the 'a' file.} Rb8 {[%cal Gb8b6,Yc7c6,Yc6d5] This is Aronian's latest try. Black prepares Rb6-Bd5-c6.} (15... b4 $2 {Would be a serious mistake, because White can now play} 16. Bb7 Rb8 17. Bxa6 $16 {[%cal Ga6c4] And the bishop can safely retreat on c4.}) (15... Bd7 {This was Aronian's first idea, but then he changed in favor of 15...Rb8, which means that 15...Bd7 was at least not fully equalizing.} 16. Bxd7 Qxd7 17. b3 $5 {This is a very useful move for us.} (17. Qd2 $6 {[%csl Rd2][%cal Rf3d2] Was played by many strong players, but I don't like this move because we need to keep free the d2 square for our knight.}) 17... c5 18. Nd2 $1 {[%csl Gd2] Our knight is well placed on d2, because it is prepared for Black's main idea d6-d5.} d5 19. axb5 axb5 20. exd5 Qxd5 21. Qg4 $14 {[%cal Ga1a7,Gd2e4,Gf1a1] We can continue with Ra7, or Ne4, and it's clear that we have a pleasant advantage.}) 16. h3 {We immediately force Black to take a decision. Now, all the three bishop's moves are possible.} Be6 {This move was played by Aronian against Caruana in 2017.} (16... Bd7 {is the most simple one for us, because after} 17. Bxd7 Qxd7 18. b3 $14 {[%csl Gf3,Rf6] We have a typical position where our knight is more useful than Black's bishop on f6.}) (16... Bc8 17. axb5 axb5 18. Ra5 {We go after the b5 pawn.} Rb6 $1 (18... b4 $6 19. Qd2 $16 {[%cal Gf1a1] Rfa1 next, and White dominates.}) 19. Bxb5 Be6 $14 {This is Black's best continuation, and it's a very important one for the correct evaluation of the line.} (19... c6 $2 20. Bc4 Rxb2 21. Ra8 Rb6 22. Qd2 Qc7 23. Rfa1 Rb8 24. Rxb8 Qxb8 25. Qa5 $16) 20. Nd2 $1 {[%cal Gb5c4] We prepare Bc4.} (20. Qa1 {looks logical, but Black can equalize with} c6 21. Ba4 c5 22. Nd2 Rxb2 $11) 20... d5 $1 {The critical continuation.} (20... Bg5 $6 {Looks logical, but it's not the best.} 21. Ba4 $1 Bxd2 22. Qxd2 Rxb2 23. f4 {[%cal Gf5f6,Gf4f5] f5-f6 is a serious threat, so Black has to play} f6 $1 24. Bc6 $14 {[%csl Ga5,Rd4,Gf1][%cal Gf1a1] We have the 'a' file, and Black's pawn on d4 is a target.}) 21. Ba4 dxe4 22. Nxe4 Rxb2 23. Nc5 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Ga4b3]} Rb6 24. Bb3 Bxb3 25. Nxb3 $14 {[%csl Gb3,Rf6] Of course, Black's position is not lost, but we can play a long and pleasant game because our knight is superior than Black's bishop.}) 17. axb5 axb5 18. Re1 $14 {This is my recommendation. We play this useful waiting move, and if Black plays in Aronian's style:} (18. Qd2 {[%csl Rd2] Caruana played this standard move, but after} Rb6 19. Bd5 Bxd5 20. exd5 b4 $1 21. b3 Rb5 22. Ra4 Qb8 23. Re1 Qb6 $11 {Black's position was absolutely fine, and the game ended soon in a draw.}) (18. b4 $14 {Deserves attention.}) 18... Rb6 19. Bd5 Bxd5 20. exd5 b4 {We have now the d2 square for our knight.} 21. Nd2 $14 {[%cal Gd1f3,Gd2c4,Ga1a5] We can continue with Nc4-Qf3-Ra5, and we have a pleasant game with some pressure. CONCLUSIONS: 12...Nxd5 has been regarded as a very solid defense and was frequently employed by Aronian in the past. As we've observed, Aronian continuously sought to refine this line across multiple games, but eventually, he stopped using it, suggesting that he may not have been fully satisfied with the resulting positions. From a theoretical perspective, if White has a solid grasp of the positional logic, he can look forward to a comfortable game. Black is unable to force an immediate draw and instead must defend a potentially challenging position over a likely long game.} *

