1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. d3 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. a3 {In this Chapter, we will check Black's sidelines to the most common move 8...00.} a5 $5 {This move was recently played by many strong GrandMasters like Van Foreest, Alekseenko, Warmerdam, Rapport...} (8... Be6 {we can play our typical move} 9. Nc3 $5 Bxb3 {Would be Black's independent option, but the opening of the 'c' file goes in our favor:} (9... O-O 10. Nd5 {transposes in Chapter 4.}) 10. cxb3 {Black has some problems on the c line. If he manages to play c7-c5 he will be fine, but that's not easy, as after Nb8 white has always d4} O-O 11. Be3 d5 {Black's critical continuation, but now we can play} (11... Nb8 12. d4 $1 Nbd7 13. d5 $16 {[%cal Gc1c7] We have a good play on the 'c' file.}) 12. Bg5 $1 {[%csl Gd5] Fighting for the d5 square.} d4 $1 (12... dxe4 13. dxe4 $16 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gc3d5,Yg5f6,Ye7f6]}) 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Nd5 {[%cal Ga1c1] Our idea is Rc1.} Nb8 $1 {Black's best continuation.} 15. Rc1 c6 16. Nxf6+ Qxf6 17. b4 $14 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gf3d2,Gd2b3,Gc1c6] We can continue with Nd2-Nb3, and we have a long-term initiative.}) (8... Bg4 {I don't like this move now, because White may think to play with c3.} 9. Be3 (9. c3 $5) 9... d5 {This is Black's independent option.} (9... Nd4 $6 10. Bxd4 exd4 11. h3 Bh5 12. c3 $16) (9... O-O {We can at least play} 10. Nc3 {transposing in Chapter 7, but maybe we have other interesting options.}) 10. h3 Bh5 (10... Bxf3 11. Qxf3 dxe4 12. Qg3 $1 (12. dxe4 {is also fine, but Qg3 looks stronger.}) 12... exd3 13. Qxg7 Rf8 14. cxd3 Nd4 15. Bxd4 Qxd4 16. Nc3 Qxd3 17. Rfe1 Qg6 18. Qxg6 hxg6 19. Rxe5 $16 {Black had a very unpleasant endgame in Duda-Dubov, 2021.}) 11. Nbd2 O-O 12. c3 $14 {[%csl Rh5] Black's bishop on g4 is misplaced.}) (8... Na5 9. Ba2 c5 (9... Be6 {Now, we have a lot of interesting options, but I like the following one:} 10. Bxe6 fxe6 11. c4 $14 {And White has a typical good game.}) 10. Nc3 Be6 11. Bg5 {It's the simplest for us, because after} (11. Nh4 {Is another serious continuation that was played in many games.}) 11... O-O {We transpose in Chapter 5.}) 9. c4 $5 {I like this direction, which was played only in two games, both times by MVL.} ({If we continue in our normal spirit, then after} 9. Nc3 a4 10. Ba2 Rb8 $13 {It's not so easy to fight for an advantage, and in practice, Black scored 2/3.}) 9... Bg4 {In both games, Black played Bg4.} (9... b4 $14 {Doesn't work well for concrete reasons:} 10. d4 $1 Bg4 11. Ba4 $1 {Very important move.} Bd7 12. d5 Nb8 13. c5 $1 Nxe4 14. c6 Bf5 15. Bb5 $1 {[%cal Rb8a6] Against Na6.} bxa3 (15... Na6 $6 16. Bxa6 Rxa6 17. axb4 $16) 16. Rxa3 Na6 17. Rxa5 Nb4 18. Ra3 $14) (9... bxc4 $14 {This is a solid move for Black, but not an equalizer.} 10. Bxc4 Nd4 11. Nxd4 exd4 12. Bg5 O-O 13. Nd2 $14 {We have a typical more pleasant position.}) 10. Be3 bxc4 11. Bxc4 O-O 12. h3 $14 {This is White's most ambitious continuation.} (12. Nc3 {was played twice by MVL, but after} Nd4 $1 13. Bxd4 exd4 14. Nb5 c5 $13 {Black has a good position.}) (12. Nbd2 $5 {This is safer than 12.h3, but it's also interesting. We get a non-forced position, and we have some edge.}) 12... Bxf3 (12... Bh5 $2 13. g4 Bg6 14. Nc3 $16 {[%csl Rg6] Black has a bad bishop on g6.}) 13. Qxf3 Rb8 $1 {Critical.} (13... Nd4 14. Bxd4 exd4 15. Nd2 $14 {[%csl Gc4,Re7] Typical slightly better position for White.}) 14. Nc3 $1 Rxb2 15. Rfb1 Rxb1+ 16. Rxb1 $36 {[%cal Gc3d5] Nd5 next and not only we have compensation, but also some initiative.} *

