1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. d3 d6 {This move order is less common, but it's also possible. Black tries to delay b5, and we cannot transpose to our Nc3+a3 system.} 7. c4 $5 {This is my recommendation. We take profit from the fact that Black did not play b7-b5. 7.c4 is not refuting the line, but it leads to easy-to-play positions for White with a safe small advantage, and it also forces Black to play less standard Spanish positions.} (7. Nc3 $6 {allows} b5 8. Bb3 Na5 $36 {And Black is immediately slightly better because he will have the pair of bishops.}) (7. a3 O-O 8. Nc3 {Now, Black plays without b5:} Bg4 $1 {[%cal Gc6d4] Nd4 is a serious threat, and after} 9. Be3 Nd4 10. Bxd4 exd4 11. Nd5 Nxd5 {Compared to our main lines, our bishop is still on a4, which means we cannot recapture on d5 with the bishop. By showing you 7.Nc3 and 7.a3, I want to make you understand that we cannot transpose to our main system against the Classical Spanish.}) (7. c3 {Is White's most common continuation. The idea is that whenever Black will play b5, we will play Bc2 in our move.} O-O 8. Re1 b5 ({Black can play without b5:} 8... Re8 9. Nbd2 Bf8 10. d4 $5 (10. Nf1 {allows} b5 11. Bc2 d5 $13 {Which is probably fine for Black.}) 10... b5 11. Bc2 $14 {Black is solid, but White achieves what he wants in the Spanish, and the position is for sure playable.}) 9. Bc2 d5 {This is the critical continuation.} 10. Nbd2 dxe4 11. dxe4 Be6 12. Qe2 $14 {/= These positions are slightly more pleasant for White. 7.c3 is also a very good direction, and you can use it in your games.}) 7... O-O ({Black can try to play the immediate} 7... Bg4 8. h3 {and now he has a choice.} Bxf3 (8... Bh5 {[%cal Ye8g8,Yg2g4] Black maintains the pin, but as soon as Black castles, White might consider g2-g4.} 9. Be3 O-O 10. Nbd2 $5 {Another useful move, and we can continue with g4 next:} Nd7 11. g4 Bg6 12. a3 $14 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gb2b4] We can consider b4 next, and Black's bishop on g6 is passive.}) 9. Qxf3 {[%cal Rc6d4] Black is not in time to play Nd4 because of the pin, while after} O-O 10. Be3 Nd4 11. Bxd4 exd4 12. Nd2 $14 {[%cal Gf3e2,Gf2f4] We will play Qe2-f4 with a slightly better position. Let's follow the game Saric-Vavulin, 2021.} c6 13. Qe2 Nd7 14. Bc2 (14. Bd1 $5 {[%cal Yd1f3,Yd1g4] It also deserves attention because maybe our bishop could go on f3 or g4 one day. For example:} Bf6 15. f4 g6 16. g3 Bg7 17. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5]} h5 18. Qg2 $14) 14... Bf6 15. f4 g6 {Both sides are playing standard moves.} 16. Nf3 (16. Rae1 Bg7 17. g4 $5 {[%cal Gg4g5,Gh3h4,Gh4h5] is an interesting plan suggested by the machine. White's idea is to play g5-h4-h5 and take space on the kingside.}) 16... Bg7 17. Qf2 Qb6 $6 (17... b5 $13 {Was Black's right continuation, with a balanced position.}) 18. Rab1 $1 {[%cal Gb2b4] White plans b4.} a5 19. g4 $1 {This is a good move for White in this structure. The game continued with some mistakes, but Saric showed the right plan for White:} Rae8 20. Kh1 Kh8 21. Rg1 Qd8 22. Rg2 Qb6 23. a3 Ra8 24. h4 $1 a4 25. h5 Kg8 26. g5 Ra5 27. Qh4 $18 {White got a winning position in Saric-Vavulin, 2021.}) 8. h3 {[%cal Rc8g4] We prevent Bg4.} Be6 (8... Nd4 9. Nxd4 exd4 10. Nd2 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gd2f3] our plan is f4-Nf3.} Nd7 (10... c6 11. Bc2 {we use the same idea of the 10...Rb8 variation.} b5 12. b3 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gd2f3]}) (10... Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5] Black wants to play b5, and we can continue with a prophylactic move:} 11. Bc2 $5 b5 12. b3 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gd2f3] F4-Nf3 next, and White has a better game.}) 11. Bc2 $5 {As we have already seen, this is a typical good prophylactic move for White.} b5 12. b3 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gd2f3] F4-Nf3 next.}) (8... Nd7 {The Nd7-Nc5 plan is standard in this structure.} 9. Nc3 Nc5 10. Bxc6 $1 bxc6 11. d4 exd4 12. Nxd4 Bd7 13. Be3 Bf6 14. Nde2 $14 {[%cal Gd1c2,Ga1d1] White is better from the positional point of view.}) 9. Nc3 Nd7 {[%cal Gf7f5] This time, Black doesn't play for Nc5 but for f7-f5.} 10. Be3 f5 (10... Qe8 11. Nd5 Bd8 12. d4 $14 {Durabaily-Chigaev, 2023.}) 11. exf5 Bxf5 12. d4 {Black can now choose if to allow d5 or if to take on d4.} exd4 (12... Bf6 13. d5 Ne7 14. Bc2 $14 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gc3e4] White has a very good version of the KID structure. After the exchange of the bishops, our knight will have the important e4 square.}) 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Nc5 15. Bc2 $14 {White has a typically slightly better structure and can play a long game. If you check the engine's evaluation, it is only +0,10, but everybody knows that this structure is not equal in real life.} *

