1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 {This is the starting position of the Open Spanish.} 6. Re1 $5 {My recommendation. The idea is to get a slightly more pleasant and playable position without the need to study all the big theory that arises after 5.d4.} Nc5 $1 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Gc5a4] This is Black's only good continuation.} (6... d5 $4 {Is already a huge mistake because of} 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8. d3 Nc5 9. Nxe5 $18 {Black can already resign.}) (6... Nf6 $2 {Is a bad retreat because our bishop on a4 doesn't get attacked:} 7. Nxe5 Be7 (7... Nxe5 {In 37 games out of 42, White played the natural 8.Rxe5, which loses all the advantage, but after} 8. d4 $18 {dxe5 next, and White's position is already winning.}) 8. d4 O-O 9. c4 $16 {[%cal Gb1c3] Nc3 next, and White has a big advantage.}) 7. Bxc6 (7. Nxe5 $6 Nxe5 8. Rxe5+ Be7 $15 {[%csl Ra4] Black is already slightly better because he will manage to exchange our bishop on a4 and will have then the pair of bishops in a symmetrical position.}) 7... dxc6 (7... bxc6 $2 8. Nxe5 Be7 9. d4 Ne6 10. d5 $5 (10. c4 {Is also good enough for an advantage.}) 10... cxd5 11. c4 $1 {Black cannot take on c4 because of Qf3.} O-O (11... dxc4 $4 12. Qf3 $18 {[%cal Gf3f7,Gf3a8]}) 12. cxd5 Nc5 13. Be3 $16 {White is just better.}) 8. Nxe5 {From the strategic point of view, Black is doing great because he has a solid structure and a pair of bishops, but we will try to use our lead in development to create problems. Now, Black's main move is 8...Be7 and we will consider it in the next chapter. Now, let's focus on the two sidelines: Ne6 and Be6.} Be6 {[%cal Gd8f6,Ge8c8] Black maybe plans Qf6-000.} (8... Ne6 {[%cal Gf8d6] Black may play this move with the idea of developing his bishop to d6 and not to e7, as in the main line.} 9. Qh5 $1 {We force Black to defend against our threats instead of completing the development.} (9. Qf3 {Is not interesting for us because of} Qf6 $1 {where after} 10. Qxf6 gxf6 $11 {Black's position is solid, and the pair of bishops compensate for the structural damage.}) 9... g6 {It's probably the best continuation, but it's connected with a long sequence of engine moves.} (9... Qf6 10. d4 Bd6 11. Nc3 Bxe5 (11... O-O 12. Ne4 Qd8 13. c3 $14 {Looks unpleasant for Black.}) 12. Rxe5 O-O 13. Be3 $14 {Now, Black doesn't have the pair of bishops, and we can try to press this risk-free, slightly better position.}) 10. Qf3 {Now, Black doesn't have Qf6.} f6 $1 {Black's only defence, but I don't think it's easy for a human:} (10... Qe7 $4 11. Nxc6 $18) (10... f5 $6 11. b3 $14 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gc1a3] Bb2 or Ba3 next.}) 11. Nxc6 bxc6 $1 12. Qxc6+ Kf7 $1 (12... Bd7 $6 13. Rxe6+ Be7 14. Rxe7+ Kxe7 15. Qc3 $14 {Obviously, we have more than enough compensation for the exchange. This position is very difficult for Blacks to defend in practice.}) 13. Qxa8 Nd4 $1 {Even if Black sees this resource, it will still be very difficult for him to understand that this is good.} 14. Na3 (14. Qb8 $5 {Also deserves attention because we prevent Nxc2 because of Qb3+.}) 14... Bxa3 15. bxa3 Nxc2 16. Bb2 Nxe1 17. Rxe1 Qxd2 (17... Re8 18. Rxe8 Qxe8 19. h4 Qe1+ 20. Kh2 Qxd2 21. Qxc8 Qxb2 22. Qxc7+ $14 {Objectively draw, but in a practical game, White still has chances. I remember that I won a very similar endgame a few years ago in the Olympiad.}) 18. Qe4 $1 Qd6 $1 19. Qf3 $36 {Black has to find many strong moves, which have never been played yet, to end up in a drawish but still slightly uncomfortable position. If our opponent knows so much, we can play a few more moves, and if we see that it's a draw, we will just agree to it. But I don't know how well prepared should be our opponent to execute all this...} (19. h4 $5)) 9. Qh5 $1 {[%cal Ge5f7] We threat Nxf7.} Qe7 {[%cal Ge8c8] Black continues to prepare the long castle.} (9... Qf6 $2 {not a good square for Black's queen, because of} 10. d4 $1 Nd7 11. Bg5 $18) (9... g6 10. Qf3 Be7 11. Nc3 O-O 12. b4 Nd7 13. Nxd7 Qxd7 14. Bb2 $14 {[%cal Gc3e4] Ne4 next, and Black still needs to solve some problems.}) 10. d4 Nd7 11. Bg5 Nf6 {White has now two interesting directions:} 12. Bxf6 $5 (12. Qe2 $5 {This is a more positional option.} h6 (12... O-O-O {a human move, but probably not the best.} 13. Nd2 Qb4 (13... Rxd4 $2 {is not a good idea because of} 14. Nxc6 $1 bxc6 15. Qxa6+ Kb8 16. Nb3 $16 {[%csl Rb8] And White has a serious advantage.}) 14. Ne4 Be7 15. c3 $14) 13. Bh4 g5 {this is how the engine plays with Black.} 14. Bg3 Bg7 15. Nd2 O-O 16. Ng6 $1 fxg6 17. Qxe6+ Qxe6 18. Rxe6 $14 {We have a slightly-better endgame, and Black needs to play very well to make a draw.}) 12... Qxf6 13. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3e4] Our idea is Ne4, for example:} g6 (13... O-O-O 14. Ne4 Qe7 15. Nc5 $1 Rxd4 16. Nxe6 fxe6 17. c3 $16 {[%csl Re6,Rf8,Rh8] Black has big problems with the development.}) 14. Ne4 $1 O-O-O $3 (14... Qg7 15. Qe2 {and now, the natural} O-O-O $2 {loses because of} 16. Nxc6 $1 bxc6 17. Qxa6+ Kb8 (17... Kd7 18. c4 $18 {[%cal Gd4d5] d5 next, and White is winning.}) 18. Re3 $18) 15. Nxf6 gxh5 16. Rad1 $14 {Yes, Black has two bishops, but his structure is very bad, and our knights are well-placed. According to the engine, the evaluation is +0,30, but my feeling is that in a practical game, it could be more.} *

