a strong engine may hold.}) 10. Be3 $1 {This is our idea. We defend the d4 pawn and want to continue with c4.} (10. c3 {Is White's most common continuation, but after} O-O $13 {Black's position is solid and playable, and it's difficult for us to find interesting ideas.}) 10... O-O (10... Bf6 $6 {Bf6 is almost never a good move in this line.} 11. f4 $1 O-O (11... Bxe5 12. fxe5 $14 {[%cal Gc2c4,Gb1c3] c4-Nc3 next.}) 12. c4 {trans in 10...00.}) 11. c4 {[%csl Rc8,Re6][%cal Gb1c3,Rc8e6] Let's discuss this position. Black has two bishops and a solid position. On the other hand, we have more space in the center and easier development, and we play against the fact that Black's knight on e6 is misplaced as it makes passive also the bishop on c8.} f6 $1 {In my opinion, Black has to play this move sooner or later, so it makes sense to play it immediately.} (11... Bf6 $6 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Rf7f6] This may seem like a very natural move, and it has been played by many strong players, including Mamedyarov, but the bishop on f6 is misplaced because Black loses the important resource f7-f6.} 12. f4 $1 {Our knight is very stable on e5, and it will be hard for Black to complete the development. The engine already evaluates +0,50, but let's follow some games to better understand the position.} Re8 (12... g6 {[%cal Ge6g7,Gg7f5] Black plans Ng7-Nf5.} 13. Nc3 Ng7 {Simonian-Petrosyan, 2021.} 14. Qf3 $1 Nf5 15. Rad1 $1 {We give the second bishop! because after} Nxe3 16. Rxe3 $16 {[%cal Gd4d5,Yg2g4,Yf4f5] All our pieces are very active, while Black's ones are still far behind in development. We can continue with d5 or f4-f5 (f4-g5) , and White's position is already much better.}) 13. Nc3 Nf8 {This was played in the game Asadli-Petriashvili, 2023.} 14. Qf3 $1 {Now, Bh4 is less strong, because after} ({White continued with} 14. Bf2 $6 {but after} Bh4 $1 15. g3 Bf6 $13 {[%csl Gc8,Rf2,Yf3,Yg2,Yh3][%cal Gf6e5] Black solves all the problems because he will exchange on e5, and in the resulting opposite-color bishop's position, our light squares will be quite weak.}) 14... Bh4 15. g3 Bf6 16. Rad1 {White's pieces are much better placed, and after, for example,} Bxe5 17. dxe5 Qe7 18. f5 $18 {Black faces unsolvable concrete problems.}) (11... Bd6 {The problem of this move is that White can play} 12. f4 {and when Black plays f6,} f6 13. Nd3 $1 {[%csl Rd4,Rd6][%cal Yd8d4] Is possible, because the d4 pawn is not hanging. Let's follow the high-level game Ragger-Bjerre, 2024.} Re8 (13... Be7 14. Nf2 g6 {[%cal Ge6g7] Black plans Ng7.} 15. Nc3 Ng7 {This is the game Dvirnyy-Kryzanowsky, 2010. White played Qf3 and allowed Be6. More precise would have been} 16. Qb3 $14 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Gb3b7] Not allowing Be6, and after} Nf5 17. Rad1 $1 Nxe3 18. Rxe3 $14 {[%cal Gd4d5,Gc4c5] Black has two bishops, but all our pieces are very active, and we are ready to create concrete problems by playing d5 (or c5 and then d5) .}) 14. Nc3 Nf8 {This is a standard idea for Black, but now White has already a big advantage:} 15. c5 $1 Be7 {Ragger played Qb3, but much stronger would have been} 16. Bf2 $16 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gf4f5,Rc8e6,Ye1e6] Where White already has a huge advantage because it's very difficult for Black to complete the development. If Black stays, we could play g4-f5.} Be6 $4 (16... Bf5 17. g4 $16) 17. Rxe6 Nxe6 18. Qb3 $18 {[%cal Gf4f5]}) (11... Re8 12. Nc3 Nf8 {[%csl Gf7][%cal Gf8g6] Black tries to play without f6, and wants to challenge our knight by playing Ng6.} 13. Qb3 $1 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4c5,Yb3f7] c5 is already a threat.} Ng6 {Is necessary.} 14. Rad1 $36 {It's a new position, which looks unpleasant for Black in a practical game. A human continuation could be:} Bf8 15. Ne4 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Qh4 17. Bc5 $14) 12. Nf3 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gd1b3,Ga1d1,Yd4d5] What is our idea? Nc3-Qb3-Rad1, eventually d5. It's not easy for Black to generate a counterplay because he still needs to finish the development.} f5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gf5f4,Ge7f6] This is, by far, Black's most common continuation in practice and it has been played in the 70% of the games that reached this position. It's a very human move because Black wants to continue with f4-Bf4, putting some pressure against our d4 pawn. From a psychological point of view, it's normal that Black doesn't want to play a passive position and wants to start an active counterplay, but objectively, it may not be Black's best continuation.} (12... Ng5 {This is a serious move.} 13. Nc3 $14 {What if we start with Nc3?} ({I have tried to analyze} 13. Nxg5 fxg5 14. Nc3 {but it seems to me that Black's play is easy:} Bf5 15. Qb3 Rb8 16. c5+ Kh8 17. d5 $11 {We are not worse, but also not better.}) (13. Bxg5 fxg5 14. Nc3 Bf6 $13 {[%cal Gg5g4] g4 next, and I cannot find ideas for White. But this variation gave me an idea!}) 13... Bg4 {This is Black's idea, but only now we can take on g5!} (13... Nxf3+ 14. Qxf3 $14 {[%cal Gd4d5,Ga1d1,Ge3f4] White has a very easy game: Rad1-d5-Bf4, and it's unpleasant for Black.}) 14. Bxg5 fxg5 {And the difference is that compared to 13.Bxg5, now we forced the move Bg4, and Black cannot play his standard plan Bf6-g4.} 15. Re4 $5 {My idea is to allow Bxf3-gxf3, where we will play a position with the knight versus the bishop.} Bxf3 ({if Black maintains the pin, then we can play} 15... Bh5 16. Qb3 $1 {[%cal Gf3e5] we are ready to play Ne5, so it's logical for Black to take on f3.} Bxf3 17. gxf3 {[%csl Gb3] and compared to 15...Bxf3, we got the Qb3 move for free. It's important to mention that} Rxf3 $2 {is not good because of} 18. Qxb7 $16 {[%cal Gb7c6] Qxc6 next, and White has a big advantage.}) 16. gxf3 {Of course, our kingside structure is damaged, but Black doesn't have a knight and doesn't also have a light-squares bishop to take profit of our weaknesses! Potentially, our knight could be better than Black's bishop. For example:} Qd7 {[%cal Gf8f7,Ga8f8,Ya8e8] This is probably the most logical move because Black is ready for Rae8 or Rf7-Raf8.} (16... Bd6 $6 17. c5 Bf4 {Somebody may think that f4 is a good square for the bishop, but after} 18. Qb3+ Kh8 19. Ne2 {[%csl Rb7] Black needs to take care about the b7 pawn.} b6 20. Qc3 Qd5 21. Nxf4 $1 {We exchange the light pieces to have a dominant position in a heavy-pieces middlegame.} gxf4 22. Re5 Qd7 23. Rae1 $16 {We dominate the 'e' file.}) 17. c5 {[%cal Gd1b3] we have annoying Qb3+ ideas. Black now needs to think if it's possible or not to sacrifice the b7 pawn. You know, maybe now Black can find a good counterplay if we take the pawn, but in a few moves, things may be different...} Rf7 (17... Kh8 {Black plays a prophylactic move against the Qb3+-Qxb7 idea.} 18. Qe2 {we can now change the plan.} Rf7 19. Re1 Bf6 20. Kg2 $14 {We dominate the 'e' file, and it's unpleasant to play from the Black side.}) (17... Rae8 $6 {This natural move is a mistake:} 18. Qb3+ Kh8 19. Rae1 $16 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Ge4e8] Black has problems on the 'e' file and on the b7 pawn. The engine already evaluates +1,00.}) 18. Qb3 Raf8 19. Rae1 Kh8 20. R1e2 $5 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Ge2f2] With this prophylactic move, we defend our important f2 pawn in advance.} Bd8 {This is not forced but a normal move. In these positions, we cannot analyze every single move, but I want to give you an idea of how the game can continue.} 21. Nb1 $5 {Rxf3 is impossible because of the 8th rank, while after} (21. Qxb7 $5 Rxf3 22. Qxa6 {According to the engine, Black can make a draw after g4!, but a player needs to understand it during the game!}) 21... h6 22. Nd2 $13 {[%cal Gd2f3] We have defended our pawn on f3, and Black needs now to think about his pawn on b7. According to the engine it's equal, but I think it's easier to play from the White's side.}) (12... Re8 {[%cal Ge6f8] This is Black's most solid continuation. The idea is to remove the knight from the bad e6 square by playing Nf8.} 13. Nc3 Nf8 {[%cal Gc8g4] Black plans Bg4.} (13... Ng5 $2 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gf8f3] This move is not good anymore, because after} 14. Bxg5 fxg5 15. Qb3 $16 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gc4c5,Ga1d1,Gd4d5,Gf3e5] Black's rook doesn't control the critical 'f' file as in the 12...Ng5 variation.}) (13... Bd6 {Normal looking move, but White gets the initiative:} 14. Qb3 {[%cal Gc4c5,Ga1d1,Gd4d5] We plan Rad1-c5-d5.} c5 {Black's principled continuation, but White is better after} 15. dxc5 Nxc5 16. Bxc5 $1 Rxe1+ (16... Bxc5 $2 17. Ne4 Bf8 18. Rad1 $18) 17. Rxe1 Bxc5 18. Ne4 Be7 19. c5+ Kf8 20. h3 $14 {Salinas-Sarkar, 2022.}) 14. d5 $5 {This is the most interesting try, in my opinion.} (14. Qb3 $5 {This move may be a good practical try because Black needs to find} Bg4 $1 {If he wants to fully-equalize.} 15. Qxb7 Qd7 16. d5 Bxf3 $1 (16... Bd6 $6 {Was played in the high level game Tomczak-Kollars, 2022, but after} 17. Nd2 $1 cxd5 18. Qxd5+ Be6 19. Qa5 $14 {Black doesn't have full compensation. As you see, even for a young 2635 GM it's not so easy to equalize with Black!}) 17. gxf3 Bd6 {And it seems that it's a draw:} 18. Ne4 $11 {Black has many moves like Qf5, Be5, or even Rxe4, and they all end in a draw. Maybe you will be able to find some practical ideas in this position for one or two games.}) 14... Bb4 {Engine's suggestion.} (14... cxd5 {This is a natural move for a human because Black improves his structure, but we get a strong knight on d5:} 15. Nxd5 Be6 16. Qb3 {[%cal Ga1d1] Rad1 next, and it's not easy to play with Black. Let's follow a few engine's strongest moves:} b5 $1 17. Rad1 Bd6 18. Bf4 Bxd5 $1 19. Rxd5 Rxe1+ 20. Nxe1 Qe7 21. Be3 $14 {/= Even if Black finds all these best moves, the game still continues, and White has a slight pressure.}) (14... Bg4 {Has been played in two correspondence games.} 15. Bf4 Ng6 16. Bg3 Qd7 17. h3 Bh5 18. dxc6 Qxc6 19. Nd5 Bd6 20. Rxe8+ Rxe8 21. Bxd6 Bxf3 (21... Qxd6 $2 22. g4 $18) 22. Qxf3 Qxd6 23. Rd1 $14 {Black is solid, but I guess you will agree with me that the position is not 100% equal, especially for a practical game.}) 15. dxc6 Qxd1 16. Rexd1 bxc6 17. Na4 $14 {[%cal Ge3c5,Yc4c5] /= According to the engine, Black is fine, but from a human point of view, it's clear that White has a more comfortable game. We treat now c4-c5, and if Black's bishop retreats immediately, we can play the positional move Bc5!?}) 13. Bd2 $5 {[%cal Gd2c3] My idea is to immediately play Bc3.} (13. Nc3 $5 {Is another interesting continuation.} f4 14. Bd2 Bf6 15. Ne4 $5 (15. Ne2 {Has been played by the majority of players, but after} Ng5 $13 {Black's position is more or less fine.}) 15... Bxd4 16. Nxd4 Qxd4 (16... Nxd4 $6 17. Bb4 Rf5 (17... Re8 $2 18. Nf6+ $1 gxf6 19. Rxe8+ Qxe8 20. Qxd4 $16 {[%csl Rf4,Rf6,Rg8] White has a big advantage because all of Black's pawns are weak.}) 18. Bc3 c5 19. Nxc5 Rxc5 20. Bxd4 $14 {[%csl Rg7]}) 17. Bb4 $1 Qxd1 18. Raxd1 Re8 19. f3 $14 {From a first look, it's difficult to believe that White can be better, but the engine evaluates +0,30, and when you start thinking about the position, you understand that it's not so easy to continue with Black.}) 13... Bf6 (13... f4 {it's a standard move, but there is no need to play f5-f4 against our 13.Bd2!?} 14. Bc3 (14. h3 $5 {deserves attention.}) 14... Ng5 15. Nbd2 (15. Nxg5 {would probably be my choice, because after} Bxg5 16. Qf3 Bf6 17. d5 cxd5 18. cxd5 $14 {[%cal Gc3f6,Gb1c3] White has a slightly better and very easy-to-play position. I don't want to say that 15.Nxg5 is objectively better than 15.Nbd2 played in the game, but it could better suite the style of some players.}) 15... Bg4 {We are following the game Bjerre-Meskenas, 2024. Interestingly enough, we have seen earlier the game Ragger-Bjerre, played in February 2024. This time, Bjerre is playing White in August 2024, probably because he understood the big practical strenght of this variation. Jonas Bjerre is a young GM from Denmark with a rating above 2650 and his is very well-prepared in openings. A very good sign for our line!} 16. h3 Bh5 17. Kh2 $5 {Bjerre played Qe2, but this prophylactical move might be White's best chance. For example:} Bf6 18. Qb3 Nxf3+ 19. Nxf3 Bxf3 20. gxf3 $14 {[%csl Gh2] Obviously, the king on h2 is an improvement for White.}) 14. Bc3 {Black can play many moves, but the feeling is that it's much easier to play from the White side. For example:} b5 {This is Balck's best move, according to the engine.} (14... Ng5 $6 15. Nxg5 Bxg5 16. Nd2 $14 {[%cal Gd2f3,Gd1c2,Ga1d1] Nf3-Qc2-Rad1 next. White has a better position and a very easy play.}) 15. Qb3 bxc4 16. Qxc4 Qd5 17. Nbd2 {Only +0,15, according to the engine, but White has a very easy play.} Re8 {was played in the game Niedbala-Kusa, 2022.} 18. Ne5 $5 {[%cal Ge5c6]} Qxc4 19. Nexc4 Rd8 20. Nb3 Nxd4 21. Bxd4 Bxd4 22. Rad1 c5 23. Nxc5 $14 {White has a risk-free endgame, where Black needs to play very well to make a draw. CONCLUSIONS: 6.Re1!? is definitely not refuting the Open Spanish, but it's a very easy-to-learn variation, where White doesn't run any risk and can put pressure almost everywhere. You don't need to deal with the ocean of theory of the 6.d4 mainline, but you can still create problems for your opponent in an unknown for him territory. As we have seen, even very strong GrandMasters are often getting worse positions when playing from the Black side.} *

