1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 {The Berlin is my first-choice variation against the Spanish when I play from the Black's side. It's a very solid opening that aims to achieve comfortable positions where White doesn't have too many ideas to create problems. A few months ago, I have created a course for Modern Chess "Berlin Defense for Black".} 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1 {It's too early to comment on this move. You have likely seen hundreds of games in the 5.Re1 variation, but the vast majority of them have very little to do with what will be my main recommendation.} (5. d4 {Is White's main continuation, and it leads to the famous Berlin endgame after} Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {This endgame is extremely complex, and in recent years, Black has found many different ideas to avoid the highly theoretical main lines. If you want to play this endgame for the White's side, you need to invest a lot of time studying all the typical ideas, and then you need to be prepared against each Black's system. It's a very hard work, and in the best scenario, you will be able to achieve a slightly better, playable position. Considering that Black is objectively fine everywhere, I personally consider this work very unpractical.}) 5... Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bf1 Nxe5 {This is, by far, Black's most common continuation.} (7... Nf5 {Is the move that I am recommending in my "Berlin for Black" Modern Chess course. We will speak about it separately.}) 8. Rxe5 O-O 9. d4 Bf6 {More than 3000 games have been played in this position, but we do not need to study all this big theory because we will play the very rare} ({Black sometimes plays} 9... Ne8 {and I like now} 10. d5 $5 (10. c4 $5 {It's more concrete and more known, but it could be another interesting direction, for example:} Bf6 11. Re1 d5 12. cxd5 Qxd5 13. Be3 $14 {[%cal Gb1c3] Nc3 next. There are some games, and you can study them. This position is very concrete, and it's still a question if Black is able to fully equalize or not.}) 10... Bc5 {Black takes the chance to activate his bishop.} (10... Bf6 11. Re1 $14 {We have a better version of the 9...Bf6 10.Re2 Nf5 line, because our rook on e1 is better placed when we have our pawn on d5.} (11. Re2 {Is less strong, but it would just transpose in Chapter 15.})) 11. Re1 d6 12. Nc3 Bf5 (12... f5 $6 {Aronian played it sometimes, but objectively it's not a great move:} 13. Be3 Bxe3 14. Rxe3 Nf6 {Giri-Aronian, 2018. Now, we can improve the game with} 15. Nb5 $14 {[%csl Re6][%cal Gb5d4] Our idea is Nd4, and Black will have problems because of the weak e6 square.}) 13. Ne4 Bxe4 (13... Bb6 14. Qf3 Bg6 15. Bd2 $14 {Is unpleasant for Black.}) 14. Rxe4 Nf6 (14... f5 15. Rf4 $1 {[%cal Gb2b4] our idea is b4.} a5 $1 {[%csl Yb4][%cal Ya5b4,Rb2b4] Black prevents b4.} (15... Nf6 $6 16. b4 Bb6 17. a4 $1 a5 18. bxa5 Rxa5 19. Bd2 Ra8 20. a5 $14) 16. Bd3 g6 17. Qf3 Qd7 $1 ({the logical} 17... Nf6 {allows} 18. Bxf5 $5 (18. Bd2 {is also fine and after} Qd7 {it transposes to 17...Qd7.}) 18... gxf5 19. Rxf5 Nd7 20. Qg3+ Kh8 21. Bh6 Qe7 22. Bxf8 Rxf8 23. Rxf8+ Qxf8 24. Re1 $36 {According to the engine, Black should hold, but I don't know how many players would like to play this position form the Balck's side.}) 18. Bd2 Nf6 19. Rf1 $14 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gf1f2] A fantastic prophylactic move. What is the idea? Sometimes, in the future, Black might play Ne4, where after Bxe4-fxe4, the 'f' file opens, and White might have problems with the f2 pawn. We can now play a long game with the pair of bishops.}) 15. Rf4 $14 {[%csl Gc1,Gf1][%cal Yb2b4,Yc1b2] It's a fresh position, where I like White's chances because of the pair of bishops. For instance, we are ready to play b4-Bb2.}) 10. Re2 $5 {This move has been tried in only 150 games, but it completely changes the dynamics of the position compared to the big main line 10.Re1.} ({Why 10.Re2 is so much different than 10.Re1? This is the first logical question that we need to answer.} 10. Re1 {Black's main move is now} Re8 {after which it is extremely difficult for White to find ideas.} 11. Bf4 {is a very critical direction, but Black is fine after} Rxe1 $1 12. Qxe1 Ne8 {[%cal Gd7d5] Black is ready for d5, and if we prevent it by playing} 13. Nc3 {Black can play} Bxd4 $1 {Where there are a lot of high-level games, but Black equalizes with concrete moves.} (13... d5 $4 14. Nxd5 $18 {is White's idea.})) 10... b6 {[%cal Gc8a6] This is Black's most common continuation, and we will analyze it in Chapter 16.} (10... Re8 {As we have just seen, this is Black's most common continuation against 10.Re1, but is it so good also here?} 11. Bf4 Rxe2 12. Qxe2 Ne8 (12... Bxd4 $6 13. Bxd6 cxd6 14. Na3 $14 {Very unpleasant position for Black.} Bxb2 $4 {Is not working because of} 15. Re1 $18 {And White is winning.}) 13. Nc3 {[%csl Ge2]} Bxd4 {Do you remember this position? We had exactly the same position in the 10.Re1 note, only that White's queen was on e1. Here, the difference is huge:} (13... d6 $1 {Is Black's only way not to lose immediately, but after} 14. Nd5 $14 {White obviously has an edge.}) 14. Re1 $1 Nf6 15. Nd5 $18 {And White is winning. We have just seen the main idea of our 10.Re2!?: the standard continuation 10...Re8 is not as good now as it was before. That's why Black usually tries to play something else.}) (10... Ne8 {[%cal Gd7d5] Black prepares d5, but we can now prevent it by playing} 11. d5 $14 {[%csl Re8] And Black has a worse version of the 10...Nf5, which we will see in the next chapter, because the knight on e8 is clearly misplaced.}) (10... Nf5 {will be analyzed in Chapter 15.}) (10... Nc4 {will be analyzed in Chapter 17.}) *

