1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1 Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bf1 Nxe5 8. Rxe5 O-O 9. d4 Bf6 10. Re2 Nf5 {This is not a bad move, but after} 11. d5 $5 {Black's position is slightly uncomfortable.} d6 (11... Re8 {was played in the recent game Safarli-Sahib, 2024.} 12. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2e4]} Nd6 13. Rxe8+ $5 Qxe8 14. a4 a5 15. Ra3 $14 {[%cal Ga3e3,Gf1d3] We can continue with Re3-Bd4, eventually c4, and we have a pleasant advantage.}) (11... c6 $6 {Is premature because we can develop know our knight on c3.} 12. Nc3 d6 (12... Bxc3 $6 13. bxc3 $14 {[%csl Gc1,Rc6,Gf1] Bxc3 is good for Black only when he can place the pawns on b6-c7-d6 (as we will see after 11...d6 12.Nc3) , but after c6, the position is more open and the pair of bishops will have an influence.}) 13. Bf4 $14) 12. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2e4] Our idea is Ne4.} (12. Nc3 {Is not a good move now, because after} Bxc3 $1 13. bxc3 b6 $13 {Black's structure is very solid, and it's difficult for us to activate our bishops.}) 12... c6 $1 {This is Black's right plan, and it makes sense to go for it immediately.} (12... Bg5 $6 {This looks like a logical move, but after} 13. Ne4 Bxc1 14. Rxc1 $14 {[%cal Gd1d2,Gc1e1] White has a risk-free advantage thanks to the extra space. For example:} Bd7 15. Qd2 Re8 16. Rce1 Qh4 {Black tries to connect the rooks.} 17. g3 Qh6 18. Qb4 $5 b6 19. h4 $14 {White has some serious pressure.}) (12... Bd7 {Sooner or later Black has to play c6; that's why the immediate 12...c6 looks to me as Black's best continuation. Let's see what happens if Black tries to play without c6:} 13. Ne4 Be5 14. c3 h6 $5 {It's difficult to offer moves for Black if he wants to play without c6, but let's imagine that he will play a lot of useful moves.} (14... Bb5 15. Re1 Bxf1 16. Kxf1 $14 {We are fine with this exchange, and our position continues to be preferable.}) 15. Qd3 Re8 16. Bd2 g6 17. Rae1 Bg7 18. g3 $14 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5,Gf1h3] We can continue with h4-h5, sometimes Bh3 will create extra pressure, and Black is solid but passive.}) 13. Ne4 Be5 $1 {[%csl Yf4][%cal Rc1f4,Ye5f4] Black doesn't allow Bf4.} (13... Be7 $6 14. Bf4 $14 {[%csl Rd6] We have a nice pressure against the d6 pawn.}) 14. c3 {[%csl Yd4,Re5][%cal Yc3d4] This is a good move because we limit Black's bishop, and we take control of the d4 square. We are playing for a minimal risk-free advantage, and it's important for us not to allow Black to concretely equalize.} h6 {This useful move was played by So Weasley, and we know that he is a very well-prepared player.} (14... cxd5 {This move is premature, in my opinion.} 15. Qxd5 Ne7 {This looks like a logical move, and it allows me to show how a real game could continue.} (15... Be6 $2 {Was a mistake played in the blitz game Vitiugov-Naryanan, 2020.} 16. Qxb7 $16) 16. Qb3 d5 17. Ng5 {[%cal Gg5f3]} Bc7 18. Nf3 h6 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Gh6g5]} (18... Bg4 $2 19. Bg5 $1 f6 20. Bh4 $16) 19. Re1 $14 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gc1e3,Ga1d1,Yg2g3,Yf1g2] Our rook was no longer useful on e1. We can play a long game against Black's isolated pawn on d5.}) (14... Qb6 $14 {This move has never been played, but it looks logical.} 15. a4 $5 {[%cal Ga4a5]} a5 16. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2c4] We want to play Nc4.} cxd5 {looks logical.} 17. Nf3 Bf6 18. Qxd5 $14 {We have a typically slightly better position where we can play a long game against Black's isolated pawn.}) (14... Bd7 {This move was played in the game Kovalev-Sadhwani} 15. dxc6 $1 {It's the right time for us to take on c6. Why? Because the bishop on d7 may be misplaced in that structure.} bxc6 (15... Bxc6 {Is possible, but Black should be ready to play with an isolated pawn.} 16. Ng3 Nxg3 17. hxg3 $14 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gc1e3] Be3 next. Of course, from a theoretical point of view, Black should be able to hold, but in practice, it could be unpleasant.}) 16. Qd3 $14 {[%csl Rd6,Ye5,Yf5][%cal Yg2g4,Yf2f4] Black faces some issues because the d6 pawn is defended by the strangely placed bishop on e5 and knight on f5, while d6-d5 would allow Nc5.}) 15. f4 {A logical move, which was played by MVL.} (15. dxc6 $5 bxc6 16. Qa4 {Could be another direction, for example:} Qb6 (16... Bd7 17. Nc5 $1 Bxh2+ 18. Kxh2 dxc5 19. Kg1 $14 {[%csl Gc1,Rc5,Rc6,Gf1] We have more than enough compensation thanks to our pair of bishops and to the weak Black's pawn structure.}) 17. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2c4] We plan Nc4.} Bf6 18. Nc4 Qc7 19. Ne3 $14 {/= White has a minimal advantage, and the game continues.}) 15... Bf6 16. Nxf6+ Qxf6 17. Qd3 $14 {Is an improvement, because after} (17. Re1 $6 {Was played in MVL-So, 2022, but after} Bd7 $13 {[%cal Gf8e8] Black will continue with Rfe8 and has an absolutely fine position.}) 17... Ne7 {Is probably Black's best continuation.} (17... Bd7 {Which was So's move against 17.Re1, we can play} 18. g4 $1 Nh4 19. Qg3 $14 {With a very interesting position for us.}) 18. dxc6 bxc6 19. Bd2 $13 {According to the engine, Black's position is OK, but I like our long-term chances, thanks to the pair of bishops. CONCLUSIONS: 10...Nf5 is definitely playable, and it's impossible for White to refute it. However, most Berlin players don't like it because White can get the more pleasant positions, where Black has zero chances to win, and the draw is not guaranteed at all. Very likely, we will get some position against Black's isolated 'd' pawn, which we can play for a long time and without any risk.} *

