1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1 Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bf1 Nxe5 8. Rxe5 O-O 9. d4 Bf6 10. Re2 b6 {[%cal Gc8a6] This is Black's most common and direct move against Re2, because Ba6 is now the threat.} 11. Re1 $1 {We lost a tempo, but provoked the move b7-b6. How does it affect the game after the standard Re8?} Bb7 (11... Re8 {We are playing the main position, but Black has included b6, which is not always good for him:} 12. Bf4 Rxe1 13. Qxe1 Qe7 {This is Black's most common continuation, and it was played in the Carlsen-Karjakin, WC 2016.} (13... Ne8 {[%cal Rf6d4,Ge1e4] In this position, when Black's pawn is still on b7, Bxd4 is a threat, but here, it's not possible because of the Qe4 idea. We can use this detail in our favor.} 14. Nc3 {Black cannot now play Bxd4 because of Qe4.} Bb7 15. Qd2 {[%cal Gd4d5] We prepare d5.} d5 {Black prevents d5, but he has to play with a bad bishop on b7. Black's position is very solid, but we can play claiming that the bishop on b7 is misplaced.} ({if Black plays a useful move like} 15... g6 {then after} 16. d5 $14 {We have achieved something.}) 16. Re1 {[%cal Gg2g3,Gh2h4,Gc3d1,Gd1e3] White can continue with g3-h4, Nd1-Ne3. It's impossible to analyze all Black's moves, but we have some play.} Nd6 {In all the three games that have reached this position, Black played the natural 16...Nd6.} 17. Bd3 {was played by Svane Rasmus.} (17. Be5 $14 {[%cal Gd2f4] Deserves attention. White's idea is to continue with Qf4 and increase the pressure.} Bxe5 (17... Ne4 $5 18. Bxf6 Nxf6 (18... Nxd2 19. Bxd8 Rxd8 20. Bd3 Kf8 $1 21. f3 Nc4 22. Nd1 $14 {/= The endgame is very drawish, but White still has some small chances.}) 19. Qf4 $14 {/= White has a very small pressure.}) 18. Rxe5 Qd7 19. Qf4 Re8 20. Bd3 $14 {/= Same story as before: Black is very solid, but White has the more pleasant side.}) 17... Bxd4 {Is Black's best, according to the engine.} (17... c5 $6 {was played by McShane, but after} 18. dxc5 bxc5 19. Nxd5 $1 Bxd5 20. Bxh7+ Kxh7 21. Qxd5 $14 {White had a strong initiative and won the game.}) (17... Nc4 18. Bxc4 dxc4 19. Be5 $14 {According to the engine, Black is fine, but everybody would take White in a practical game.}) 18. Bxh7+ Kxh7 19. Qxd4 Kg8 20. Qd1 $14 {/= White has the more pleasant position, but Black is very solid.}) 14. Na3 $14 {[%cal Gc2c3] This is my novelty. Compared to 14.Nc3, we keep the c3 option to defend the d4 pawn.} (14. Nc3 {was played by Karjakin, but after} Bb7 15. Qxe7 Bxe7 $11 {Black was fine.}) 14... Bb7 15. c3 {Even the engine shows a +0,30 evaluation, which is already something. Of course, Black can play a lot of moves in this kind of positions, but I will show you our key ideas.} a6 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Ga6b5] Black covers the b5 square.} (15... Re8 $6 {Looks very natural, but suddenly after} 16. Qxe7 Bxe7 17. Bxd6 Bxd6 18. Nb5 $14 {Black has some problems.}) 16. Nc2 $1 {The key aspect of the position is that Black cannot play Re8.} Qe6 {Black needs to play some useful moves.} (16... Re8 $2 17. Bxd6 $1 Qxe1 18. Rxe1 Rxe1 19. Nxe1 cxd6 20. g3 $16 {[%cal Gf1g2] Bg2 next, and White is much better in the endgame.}) 17. Bd3 g6 18. Ne3 $1 {We allow Re8.} Re8 19. Qf1 $1 {[%csl Ra6][%cal Gd3a6] Black's a6 pawn is hanging, and after} a5 20. Re1 $14 {Black faces some problems.}) 12. Bf4 {[%cal Gf4d6] We want to play Bxd6, and Black now has two possible continuations: Ne4 or Nf5.} Nf5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gf8e8,Rf5d4] Not all players are happy with the positions arising after 12...Ne4, because they may think that Black has to play precisely, and White keeps a small practical edge. By playing Nf5, Black gains a tempo against our d4 pawn and is ready to continue with Re8.} (12... Ne4 13. Nd2 {Very likely, we will have a position without knights where we have a small pressure.} Nxd2 {This is Black's most simple move.} (13... d5 14. Nf3 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Ge5] We have the e5 square, and Black's bishop on b7 is misplaced.}) (13... Re8 14. Bd3 Nxd2 15. Qxd2 Bxd4 $14 {Is Black's best continuation, according to the engine, but no player went for it.} (15... d6 16. Bb5 $1 c6 (16... Rxe1+ 17. Rxe1 Qf8 {was played twice by So, but White has an edge after} 18. Qc3 $14 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gc3c7]} c6 19. Bf1 $14 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gc3g3] We are ready for Qg3, and Black's position is unpleasant.}) 17. Bf1 $5 Qd7 18. a4 $14 {/= White had a small pressure in MVL-Giri, 2023.}) 16. Rxe8+ Qxe8 17. Re1 Qf8 $1 (17... Qd8 $6 18. Bxh7+ Kxh7 19. Qxd4 $14) 18. c3 $5 (18. Bxh7+ Kxh7 19. Qxd4 Re8 $11 {This is why 17...Qf8 is stronger than 17...Qd8.}) 18... Bf6 19. Bxc7 $14 {For the engine, this is only +0,10, but in a practical game, we can play a long game thanks to our better pawn structure.}) 14. Qxd2 d6 {[%csl Gb7] Black keeps active his bishop, and the pawn on c7 will not be hanging now.} (14... d5 $6 {is not good because we can take control of the 'e' file:} 15. Re3 $1 Qd7 (15... Re8 $2 {[%csl Rc7] is not possible because of} 16. Rxe8+ Qxe8 17. Bxc7 $18) 16. Rae1 $16 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gf4e5] We can continue with Be5, and we have a serious advantage thanks to the control of the 'e' file.}) 15. a4 $1 {[%cal Ga4a5] We are ready to put pressure on the queenside by playing a5.} (15. Re3 {Was interesting against 14...d5, but here Black can just play} Re8 $11) 15... c5 $1 {Black's strongest continuation. Now, White doesn't have an objective advantage, but just a few tries.} (15... a5 {stops a5, but after} 16. Bb5 $14 {[%cal Rf8e8] Black cannot play Re8, while c6 would mean to make the b7 bishop passive.}) (15... a6 $6 {Was played in Motylev-Giri, 2017, but White is better after} 16. a5 $1 b5 17. c4 bxc4 18. Bxc4 $16) 16. c3 (16. Be3 $14 {[%cal Ga4a5] is also possible with the idea to play a5 next.}) 16... cxd4 17. cxd4 Rc8 18. a5 $5 {Two months later, in May of 2023, MVL changed in favor of this move.} (18. Ra3 {was played by MVL in March of 2023, but after} Re8 $11 {Black was doing fine in MVL-Navara, 2023.}) (18. Qb4 {is not working immediately only because of} a5 $1 19. Qxd6 Bxd4 $11) (18. Rad1 $14 {[%cal Gd2b4] Our idea is Qb4.}) 18... bxa5 $1 {is necessary for Black.} 19. Be3 {[%csl Gd4] White protects the d4 pawn.} a6 20. Bd3 $14 {[%cal Ga1a5] Could be an improvement because we are ready for Rxa5 and we have excluded the Rc2 idea.} (20. Rxa5 Rc2 $11 {MVL-So, 2023.})) 13. c3 Re8 (13... d6 $6 {After this move, White gets a more pleasant game.} 14. Nd2 Re8 15. Qc2 $1 Qd7 16. Ne4 $14) (13... Bg5 {was played against me by GM Bryant.} 14. Qg4 $1 Bxf4 15. Qxf4 g6 16. Nd2 {If you analyze with the engine, then the +0,20 evaluation may seem almost nothing, but in a practical game things are different.} Ng7 17. Bc4 {[%cal Rd7d5] my idea was to provoke d7-d5. It doesn't mean that this is White's best move, but it shows a possible way to approach the position.} (17. a4 $5 {was another good move.}) 17... Ne6 18. Qg3 d5 {[%csl Rb7] Black finally plays d5, but his bishop on b7 is now passive.} 19. Bd3 Qg5 {Very normal move, and also Black's best according to the engine.} 20. Qxg5 Nxg5 21. f4 $1 {I am just in time to create an initiative.} Ne6 22. f5 Nf4 {is necessary, but the knight on f4 looks strange, and I immediately felt a chance OTP. Again, for the engine Black's position is very holdable, but it doesn't mean that it's a 100% draw!} 23. Bc2 Rfe8 24. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3e5]} Ba6 25. Ba4 {my opponent is playing very well, and even now, he found the best move.} Re2 $1 26. Rxe2 Bxe2 27. Ne5 f6 28. Nc6 {Black is playing all the best moves so far, and the engine's evaluation is still around equal. But I am sure that all players in the world would take White.} Kf8 $6 {This is a very normal move, but the first inaccuracy. An engine can tell you the evaluation of the position considering all the best moves for both sides, but he doesn't say for whom it is easier to play!} (28... Bd3 $1 {Was Black's strongest continuation.}) 29. Re1 Re8 30. Nb4 $1 {[%csl Rd5] Suddenly, Black has some problems with the d5 pawn.} Re7 31. Bb3 {[%cal Rc7c6]} gxf5 $2 {The second and last mistake. As you can see, it doesn't require too many mistakes to lose these positions.} (31... g5 $1 {Was the best defense, with the idea} 32. Nxd5 Nxd5 33. Bxd5 Bd3 $1) 32. Nxd5 Nxd5 33. Bxd5 f4 34. Kf2 $18 {White's position is winning, and I safely converted the advantage in Basso-Bryant, 2022.}) 14. Nd2 (14. Rxe8+ $5 {Is another alternative, if you want to avoid the concrete 15...g5 variation.} Qxe8 15. Nd2 d6 16. Qc2 g6 17. Bd3 Ng7 18. Be4 $14 {/= might be slightly uncomfortable for Black.}) 14... Rxe1 (14... g6 {Brkic-Robson, 2024.} 15. Rxe8+ Qxe8 16. a4 $14 {[%cal Ga4a5] White keeps the typical small pressure of this line.}) 15. Qxe1 g5 $1 {This is Black's strongest continuation because it tries to concretely equalize.} (15... g6 {This is a very natural move, but after} 16. Ne4 Be7 17. Rd1 {[%cal Gd4d5] We are ready for d5.} d5 18. Nd2 Bd6 19. Be5 Qd7 20. Nf3 Re8 21. Qd2 $14 {White keeps the typical small pressure of this line.}) 16. Bg3 (16. Be5 d6 17. Bxf6 Qxf6 $11 {Black is fine.}) 16... Nxg3 ({If Black plays without Nxg3, then after} 16... c5 17. dxc5 bxc5 {White is slightly better with} 18. Be5 $14) 17. hxg3 c5 $1 {15...g5 was, of course, slightly risky from the strategic point of view, but Black justifies it with very concrete play.} (17... Qf8 {[%cal Ga8e8] Is a logical move, but White has a game after} 18. Qe2 Re8 19. Qg4 Qe7 20. Nc4 $14 {[%csl Rg5]}) 18. dxc5 $14 (18. Ne4 cxd4 19. Rd1 Bxe4 20. Qxe4 d5 $11 {Black was fine in Kryvoruchko-Aronian, 2021.}) 18... bxc5 19. Ne4 Bxe4 $1 {Necessary.} 20. Qxe4 {For the engine, this position is just equal, but Black has to be very accurate.} Rb8 $1 {Of course, I cannot change the "0.00" engine's evaluation, but I think that under some circumstances, Black's position might be risky:} (20... d5 $6 21. Qf5 $14 {White already has something.}) 21. Rd1 $5 (21. Rb1 d5 $1 22. Qf5 Qe7 23. Qxd5 Bxc3 $11) (21. Bc4 $5 Rxb2 22. Rd1 d6 23. Re1 $13 {[%cal Ge1e3,Ge3f3]}) (21. Qc2 d5 $1 22. Rd1 d4 $11) 21... Rxb2 22. Qf5 d6 23. Rd3 Kg7 24. Rf3 $13 {[%cal Gf1d3] Looks a bit risky for Black, but for the engine this is just a draw. CONCLUSIONS: Itâ€™s impossible to refute the Berlin Defense, and against 10.Re1!?, Blackâ€™s strongest continuation may be 10...b6. When Black opts for this move, our goal isnâ€™t necessarily to achieve an objective advantage but rather to create practical pressure. Weâ€™ve looked at numerous examples from games between strong Grandmasters: sometimes Black finds a way to equalize and secure a draw, but often, under sustained pressure, Blackâ€™s position begins to falter. My own game against GM Bryant illustrated this well, showing how a position that engines evaluate as "0.00" can, in practical terms, be much more challenging for Black to navigate than for White.} *

