1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1 Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bf1 Nxe5 8. Rxe5 O-O 9. d4 Bf6 10. Re2 Nc4 $5 {[%csl Gc4,Ye2][%cal Gd7d5,Rf1c4] This idea was first employed by Vladimir Kramnik in 2019. Black thinks that as 10.Re2 was played, now the knight can jump on c4, preparing the typical d7-d5 necessary move.} 11. b3 $1 {We force Black's knight to retreat on b6.} Nb6 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Gd7d5] Black will eventually play d7-d5, but the knight on b6 is not well placed.} 12. h3 $5 {[%csl Rb6,Rc8] This rare move is my recommendation. What is our idea? To play against Black's bishop on c8. We have a symmetrical position, but Black's knight on b6 is not great, and if Black starts to have problems also with the light-squares bishop, then it might be our chance to fight for an advantage.} (12. c4 $6 {Looks as a logical move, but after} d5 $36 {Black is doing great.}) (12. a4 {Was for a long time considered White's critical continuation.} Nd5 (12... d5 $6 13. a5 $14) 13. Re1 {but after, for example} d6 $13 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gf6g7,Yc7c6,Yd5c7] Black can continue with g6-Bg7 and later c6-Nc7. I was not able to find for White interesting ideas in this position.}) (12. Qd3 {This move is in the spirit of 12.h3, but Black can now play} Nd5 $1 {and after} 13. c4 {he has} Nb4 $13 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Gb4d3] Gaining a tempo against our queen. That's why I think that 12.h3 is a more precise move order compared to 12.Qd3.}) ({But is h3 just a waiting move? No, and we can understand it if right now we pass the move to our opponent.} 12. d5) 12... d5 {This is Black's most logical move, and now we play} (12... Nd5 $6 {This move was good after 12.Qd3, but now we can play} 13. c4 Ne7 {Is Black's best, according to the engine, but after} (13... Nb4 {And Black's knight on b4 is attacking nothing, and we can just play} 14. Nc3 $14 {With a better position.}) 14. Nc3 c5 15. Ba3 $1 (15. Be3 $6 Nf5 $13) 15... Bxd4 {We can play the fantastic} (15... d6 16. Rc1 Bxd4 17. Nb5 $14 Be5 $2 18. Bxc5 $16) 16. Qxd4 $3 cxd4 17. Bxe7 dxc3 {Black's best idea is to give back the queen.} (17... Qa5 $6 {If Black decides to keep the queens, then after} 18. b4 Qh5 19. Bxf8 Kxf8 20. Rae1 f5 21. Nd5 $16 {White has a serous advantage thanks to the very active pieces.}) 18. Bxd8 Rxd8 19. Rc1 $14 {We have a very pleasant endgame and it's absolutely clear that Balck did not equalize.}) (12... Re8 {Was tried by GM Goganov.} 13. Rxe8+ Qxe8 14. a4 $1 {[%cal Ga4a5] We play against Black's misplaced knight on b6.} a5 {[%csl Gb5] Black stops a5, but weakens the b5 square.} (14... d5 15. a5 Nd7 16. Be3 $14 {[%cal Gc2c4,Yb1c3] c4-Nc3 next, and White has an advantage}) 15. Na3 c6 {[%csl Rb6] Black stops Nb5, but now the b6 square is weak.} 16. Nc4 $1 Nxc4 (16... Nd5 $2 17. Ba3 $18) 17. bxc4 d5 18. c5 $14 {[%csl Ra5,Yb7][%cal Ga1b1,Yb1b7] We'll place a rook on the 'b' file, and Black's a5 pawn might be weak in the long-term.}) 13. Qd3 $1 {[%csl Rc8,Rf5,Rg4][%cal Gd3f5,Gh3g4,Rc8g4,Rc8f5] We play against Black's bishop c8.} (13. Bf4 {Gives nothing, because after} Bf5 $11 {Black was absolutely fine in MVL-Giri, 2023.}) 13... Be6 {This is Black's most natural move.} (13... c5 {It's a critical move.} 14. Ba3 Nd7 15. Nc3 Bxd4 (15... Qa5 16. Bc1 Bxd4 17. Bd2 $1 {[%cal Gc3d5] Black's best move is now} Qa6 $3 18. Qxa6 bxa6 19. Rae1 Bb7 20. g4 $14 {[%cal Gf1g2] Bg2 next, with some pressure.}) 16. Rd1 Qa5 17. Nb1 $14 {[%cal Gc2c3] c3 next, and Black's position looks unpleasant. For example:} Nb6 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gb6d5] Black defends the d5 pawn.} 18. c3 Bf6 19. Qe3 $14 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Ge3c5] We will capture on c5 and will play a slightly better position thanks to the better structure.}) (13... Re8 14. Rxe8+ Qxe8 15. a4 a5 16. Bf4 c6 17. Nd2 $14 {[%cal Gd2f3,Ga1e1] Nf3-Re1 next, and our pieces are more active. Is it enough to win the game? It is difficult to say, but Black's position is unpleasant, and he needs to find good moves not to get worse.}) 14. Nd2 $14 {[%cal Gd2f3] We want to develop our knight to the natural f3 square.} (14. Bf4 {Was played in MVL-Harikrishna, 2023, but after} c5 $1 15. Be5 Rc8 $13 {Black has enough counterplay, even if I must say that the position is still playable.}) 14... Qd7 {[%cal Ge6f5,Ga8e8] This is the most natural move, because Black prepares Bf5 or Rae8.} (14... c5 {Is a logical move.} 15. Nf3 Rc8 16. Bf4 $36 {[%csl Rc5] Black's position is playable, but we can continue with Rd1 and have some initiative. In general, when Black plays c7-c5, he tries to concretely equalize, but if we are able to stabilize the position, the c7-c5 move might increase our winning chances because the position becomes more concrete.}) (14... Nc8 $5 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gc8d6] Logical move: Black wants to rotate the knight to d6.} 15. Nf3 Nd6 16. Bf4 Bf5 17. Qc3 $14 {[%cal Ga1e1] We can continue with Rae1 and control the only open file. Of course, Black is solid, but he did not fully equalize as he would wish by playing the Berlin defense.}) 15. Nf3 Bf5 16. Qc3 Rfe8 17. Ne5 $14 {[%cal Gc1f4] Bf4 next, and we have a plus, thanks to the much better-placed knight. CONCLUSIONS: 10...Nc4 is an original idea invented by Kramnik, but with our move 12.h3!? We pose serious practical problems and I don't see a clear way for Black to solve all the problems.} *

