1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1 Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bf1 O-O 8. d4 Nf5 {This is the variation I am offering for the Black side in my Modern Chess course "Berlin for Black": By playing 8...Nf5, Black wants to keep more pieces on the board, hoping to increase his winning chances, which are close to zero in the 7...Nxe5 mainline.} 9. Nf3 $1 {This is a very important move. We keep more pieces on the board.} d5 10. Nc3 {[%csl Ge1,Rf5] We have a symmetrical structure where we are slightly ahead in development, and Black has a slightly misplaced knight on f5.} Bb4 {This is Black's most common continuation and also my favorite one.} (10... h6 {This neutral move allows us to see White's typical ideas in the position.} 11. Ne2 $1 Bd6 {[%cal Gf5h4,Yf3h4,Yd8h4] This is a standard move for Black. The idea is to continue with Nh4, where after Nxh3, Black can recapture with the queen.} (11... g5 $6 {Is premature, after} 12. h4 $40 {White has a very strong initiative.}) 12. Nf4 $1 (12. Bf4 $6 {Is a harmless continuation:} Qf6 13. Bxd6 Nxd6 $11 {Black is perfectly fine.}) 12... Nh4 {Black indirectly defends the pawn on d5 because of the Nxf3+-Qxf3-Nxd4 threat.} (12... Nfe7 13. c3 Bf5 14. Nh4 Bh7 15. Nh5 Nf5 16. Nf3 $36 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gg2g4,Yf3e5]}) (12... Nce7 13. a4 a5 14. Bd3 c6 15. c3 Qc7 16. Nh5 $36) 13. Nxh4 Qxh4 14. g3 Qf6 15. c3 Ne7 16. Nh5 $14 {[%csl Gh5] This is a typical idea in the variation.} Qg6 17. Bf4 {[%cal Gf1d3] Black's position is unpleasant.} c6 {This would be a normal move.} (17... Bg4 $1 {Strongest, according to the engine.} 18. Be2 Bxe2 19. Qxe2 $14 {[%cal Ge2b5] But we have immediate threats on the 'e' file, and Qb5 is another strong idea.}) 18. Bd3 Bf5 19. Bxd6 Qxd6 20. Bxf5 Nxf5 21. Re5 $1 {As often happens, White is just in time to create an initiative.} Qg6 $1 (21... g6 $2 22. Qg4 $1 Ng7 23. Nxg7 Kxg7 24. Rae1 $18 {This is a very instructive position. According to the engine, White is objectively winning thanks to the domination on the 'e' file.}) 22. Nf4 Qf6 23. Qg4 Nd6 24. Rae1 Rae8 25. h4 $14 {Black's position is unpleasant.}) (10... Nh4 {This is a standard move in the 8...Nf5 Berlin. Normally, Black would prefer to play Bd6 first so that after Nh4-Nxh4, he can recapture with the queen.} 11. Nxh4 Bxh4 12. Bb5 $5 {[%cal Gb5c6] This is my recommendation. We threat Bxc6, after which we can play an interesting structure.} Ne7 {Black doesn't allow Bxc6. We can now follow a very instructive game played by So against Nakamura.} (12... Bf5 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. Bf4 $14 {[%cal Gc3a4,Gd1d2] We can play Na4-Qd2, and have a long game with some pressure.}) 13. Bd3 Bf6 14. Qh5 $1 g6 15. Qf3 Bg7 (15... Bxd4 $6 {Is risky because of} 16. Nb5 Bg7 17. Bg5 Be6 18. Qf4 $14) 16. Bg5 $1 {White provokes the sad f7-f6.} f6 17. Bd2 c6 18. Ne2 (18. Na4 $5 {Was another interesting direction, suggested by the engine. For example:} Nf5 19. Nc5 $5 Nxd4 20. Qf4 Nf5 21. Bxf5 Bxf5 22. Nxb7 Qb6 23. Nd6 Bxc2 24. Rac1 Qxb2 25. Re7 $36) 18... Nf5 19. g3 {[%cal Gh2h4] White prepares h4 and in a practical game, it's hard to play from the Black's side also for a GM like Nakamura.} Nh6 $6 {This was the first inaccuracy.} (19... Re8 {Was probably Black's best continuation.} 20. h4 Bh6 $1 21. Bxh6 Nxh6 22. c4 Bg4 23. Qf4 dxc4 24. Bxc4+ Kg7 25. Nc3 $36 {White has an initiative, but Black should hold.}) 20. c4 $1 {[%cal Ra2g8] c2-c4 is a typical move when Black already has weakened the a2-g8 diagonal by playing f6.} Bg4 21. Qg2 dxc4 $2 {Second mistake.} (21... Re8 $1 {Was Black's best continuation, but for a human, it looks unpleasant:} 22. cxd5 Qxd5 $1 (22... cxd5 $4 23. Bb5 $1 Re7 24. Nc3 $18) 23. Qxd5+ cxd5 24. Bb5 $14 {[%cal Ge2f4] Nf4 next, and it's not easy for a human to understand if Black can hold or not. The engine gives only +0,35.}) 22. Bxc4+ Kh8 23. d5 (23. Bc3 $16 {[%cal Ge2f4] Was also good enough, with the idea Nf4 next.}) 23... Nf7 24. Nf4 Ne5 25. Be2 Bd7 26. Rad1 cxd5 27. Bc3 Bc6 28. Nxd5 $16 {It's clear that White has an edge, and So finally won the game in So-Nakamura, 2019.}) 11. a3 Ba5 {This is Black's standard continuation, and in my course "Berlin for Black" I mention a strong novelty for Whtie, which of course will be my recommendation in this occasion.} (11... Bxc3 {Is also possible, but not all players are ready to play without the pair of bishops.} 12. bxc3 Nd6 13. Ne5 Bf5 $14 {This is probably Black's best continuation.} (13... Ne7 $6 {Hovhannisyan-Bosiocic, 2017.} 14. c4 $14 dxc4 (14... f6 15. c5 $16) 15. Nxc4 $16) (13... Re8 {Michalik-Piorun, 2023.} 14. Qf3 $1 Be6 15. a4 $36) 14. a4 {[%cal Ga4a5,Gc1a3] We prepare a5 or Ba3.} Re8 15. a5 a6 16. Bf4 $14 {White has an initiative. It's important to mention that after} Nxe5 {Our idea is to recapture with the pawn.} 17. dxe5 $1 Nc4 18. g4 Be6 19. h3 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5] We can play for the f4-f5 plan.}) 12. Bg5 $14 {We provoke f6.} f6 (12... Qd6 $6 {Would be a mistake because after the standard moves} 13. b4 Bb6 14. Ne2 Nce7 15. g4 $1 {[%csl Rd6,Rh6][%cal Rf5h6,Rf5d6] Black's knight has to go on the sad h6 square as the d6 square is no longer available.} Nh6 16. Bf4 Qd8 17. h3 $16 {[%csl Rh6]}) 13. Bf4 g5 {This is Black's critical continuation, and White's fantastic idea is} (13... Nce7 {Is Black's standard continuation, but after} 14. b4 Bb6 15. Na4 c6 16. c4 $14 {White has very good chances.}) 14. Bc1 $1 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gc3a4,Gc2c4] We lost two tempi (Bg5-Bf4) , but we provoked f6-g5, which are weakening Black's kingside.} Bb6 $1 {It seems that White has problems with the d4 pawn, but the engine shows a very strong move} (14... Nce7 {This is a standard move for Black, but here, White has a concrete continuation, which creates problems.} 15. b4 Bb6 16. Na4 c6 17. c4 $1 Bc7 18. Nc5 $14) 15. Bd3 $1 {Where Black cannot take the pawn on d4 for concrete reasons.} (15. Na4 Ncxd4 $13) 15... Ng7 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gc8g4] Black prepares Bf5 or Bg4.} (15... Nfxd4 $2 16. Nxd4 Bxd4 17. Qh5 $16) 16. Ne2 Ne7 $1 {In my "Berlin for Black" course, I stop here saying that the position is unclear, but this is probably White's best try.} (16... Bf5 $6 17. h4 $16) (16... Bg4 17. c3 $1 Bxf3 18. gxf3 $14 {[%cal Gf3f4] We will continue with f4 next.}) 17. c4 $5 {[%csl Gc4,Rf6] We already know that c2-c4 is a good idea when Black has played f7-f6.} c6 {Black's most solid continuation.} (17... dxc4 $6 {Is a bit risky.} 18. Bxc4+ Be6 19. Bxe6+ Nxe6 20. h4 $1 g4 21. Nd2 $36 {[%cal Gd2c4] Nc4 next.}) 18. Ng3 Ng6 $1 {According to the engine, this is Black's only continuation that keeps a good numerical evaluation. After other moves, White has an edge.} ({For example} 18... Kh8 {looks like a normal useful move, but after} 19. b3 $14 {[%cal Ga1a2,Ga2e2] White prepares Ra2-Rae2 and has an edge.}) 19. Qc2 {Black should now find the very strong} Bg4 $3 20. Bxg6 hxg6 21. Qxg6 Qd7 22. cxd5 cxd5 23. Qd3 Nf5 $14 {/= The engine evaluates +0,20, which means that Black has a good compensation, but White still keeps some chances.} *

